<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Police Baffled by Cape Town Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- South African police Sunday were
still unable to establish what kind of bomb was used in Friday's car bomb
explosion at Cape Town's premier tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
Police have offered a 50,000-Rand (8,600-U.S. Dollar) award for
information leading to the arrest and conviction of the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the blast which injured five
people. Three people were treated at the scene and two others were treated
for shock.
</P>
<P>
In most of the 70 explosions which occurred in the Western Cape
Province last year, pipe bombs were used, according to South African Press
Association (SAPA).
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted police spokeswoman Anine de Beer as saying that police were
still studying photographs and video footage of the blast.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately the revolving security camera near the blast was turned
away when the explosion occurred, but it did record the scene prior to, and
after the explosion, and could contain valuable clues," de Beer said.
</P>
<P>
She said police believed the bomb was placed in the boot of a stolen
Toyota which was parked near the entrance to Victoria wharf.
</P>
<P>
She confirmed that police were aware that the recently released
Hollywood movie, The Siege, was showing at the waterfront in which Islam
and Moslems were portrayed as terrorists, adding that police would look
into all possibilities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Moslem community in South Africa expressed
strong disapproval of distributing the movie in South Africa and demanded
an apology from Ster Kinekor, South Africa's largest cinema chain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
