<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-03 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Wounded in Israeli Air Raids on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Seven people, including a
Lebanese mother and her four daughters, were wounded on Sunday in
Israeli air raids on Lebanon's eastern Bekaa Valley, the Orient
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted security sources as saying that Israeli jets
fired two air-to-surface missiles at a radio station run by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, near the country's
ancient Roman city of Baalbek in Bekaa.
</P>
<P>
The group's Voice of the Oppressed radio station, whose
transmitter was damaged during the air attack, went off the air,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli jets also fired four missiles at the hills around
the villages of Nabi Sheet and Janta, about 23 kilometers
southeast of Baalbek.
</P>
<P>
A 55-year-old woman and her four daughters were wounded in the
raid in Janta, scene of the Israeli air raids on December 20, in
which a mother and her six children were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli jets also injured a Hezbollah member and a Syrian
worker who happened to be walking in the area.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, the Israeli army spokesman confirmed the attack,
saying its jets blasted terrorist bases, including a Hezbollah
radio station.
</P>
<P>
Following the raids, Hezbollah's Vice Secretary-General Naiim
Gausem announced in Baalbek that his group reserved the right to
respond and will chose a proper time and ways for retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Israeli attack came three days after its security cabinet
decided to attack Lebanon's infrastructure if and when its north
was hit again by Hezbollah's Katyusha attack.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli decision followed the group's Katyusha attack on
Israel's northern areas to revenge the killing of Lebanese
civilians in Janta, wounding at least 16 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli occupation troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
