<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Analysts Discuss Effects of Euro on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The launching of the European single
currency Euro Saturday will affect the value of Nigerian
currency Naira and Nigeria's foreign trade and other industries, according
to local analysts.
</P>
<P>
A special report carried by Sunday Tribune quoted R.O. Bakare of Unic
Insurance as saying that since the value of the Pound Sterling which is the
strongest of all European currencies is bound to fall, the development
would force the Naira to gain strength in the world market.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the appreciation of the Naira would cause the prices of
imported items from European countries to fall, and this would be a boost
for individuals and companies in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
On how the Euro would affect insurance industry, Bakare said, since
insurance companies pay their premium through foreign exchange, the
appreciation of the local currency automatically means that insurance
companies would have to pay less.
</P>
<P>
V.O. Akinola of the Nigeria Arab Bank told the paper that dealing with
such a currency would not be easy, adding that Nigeria may have a lot of
problems deciding on the terms of trade and measurement of exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the issue of European single currency, a manager of
Afribank said the Euro would create some sort of monopoly in the European
market, which means Nigeria would have limited choice to make.
</P>
<P>
For example, he explained, in the new arrangement, Nigeria and other
countries willing to buy from Europe would not have the privilege of
dictating the country whose goods they prefer.
</P>
<P>
He said the Euro would have substantial effect on the banking system in
the west African country, adding that just as the U.S. Dollar is being used
as the unit of measurement because of its prominence in the world market,
the Euro may also become a standard of measurement as it is also likely to
gain more economic power and prominence.
</P>
<P>
Tayo Fagade, a financial analyst, was quoted as saying that the
introduction of the Euro may not have serious implication of the Nigerian
economy other than an easier foreign exchange system for Nigerian importers.
</P>
<P>
He cited the example of the recent crash of the Southeast Asian
economies with the attendant effects on the global economy which
accordingly affected Nigeria's economy.
</P>
<P>
"By and large, it will now be easy to do business with any member of
the European Union without any problem of foreign exchange since a single
currency would be in use," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
