<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Pays Closer Attention to Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is paying more
attention to agricultural production in the new year.
</P>
<P>
 The government has decided to invest 600 million Kwacha(250,000 U.S.
Dollars) in the Zambia National Service (ZNS) and 246 million Kwacha(100,
000 Dollars) in the Prisons Service. Both are major agricultural
institutions in the country and have strong production bases.
</P>
<P>
 With thef money, the two organizations will be able to redouble their
efforts in improving their production.
</P>
<P>
 It has often been said that agriculture should be Zambia's economic
backbone and that the sector should be given the due support to develop to
levels that would truly make it the country's major source of livelihood.
</P>
<P>
 For long, however, the sector has either been mismanaged or merely
given lip-service.
</P>
<P>
 Today, even local farmers are in a dilemma as imported farm produce is
being preferred over local products. Several supermarkets imported produce
like tomatoes, carrots, oranges and even cabbages.
</P>
<P>
 Under such situation, the two institutions are being revamped.
With proper management they can make a major difference in the country's
agricultural production and supply to consumers. The two already have a
strong foundation and all that will be needed is to build an equally
strong structure.
</P>
<P>
 The private sector too seems to be on the right path but needs further
encouragement to improve its production. The problem, however, is that
cheaper imported products push some of the local produce out of business.
</P>
<P>
 This will soon be a thing of the past, Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi
 said,
as measures are being put in place to have more local products sold in
supermarkets and to tighten importation of farm produce, Zambia's
newspaper Sunday Mail reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
