<HEADLINE> Saddam Chairs Cabinet Meeting on U.S. Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Sunday chaired the first cabinet session of this year on Sunday
to discuss his government's position toward the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Saddam accused the U.S. of spreading false information to "calm
the Arab public opinion rejective of such imperialistic
Anglo-American onslaught on Iraq."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the U.S. allegation that it did not attack
Iraqi sites first, but the Iraqi air defense force started firing
at U.S. planes, according to the Iraqi News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
"What these planes are doing in flying over a state of
sovereignty and independence and why this state's air spaces are
being violated for eight years in time when the U.N. does not
issue a resolution endorsing such an act?" INA quoted Saddam as
asking.
</P>
<P>
The president added that such an act indicated a flagrant
breach of the U.N. Security Council resolutions which, although
being unjust, did call for respect to Iraq's integrity, political
independence and unity.
</P>
<P>
On the deferment of the Arab summit Yemen had called for,
Saddam said the purpose behind such postponement was to dismember
the Arab attitude regarding such an onslaught on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
An Arab summit had been scheduled for the end of last year to
discuss the Arab position pertaining to the December 16-19
U.S.-British air strike against Iraq, but it was put off because
of objection of some Gulf Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Saddam said if the summit was being held during the air
strikes on Iraq by U.S. missiles, the Iraqi question would be the
sole one, but the postponement of the summit would indulge Arab's
attitude into a long list of issues.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that those who postponed the summit would hope
that the Arab stand toward the assault on Iraq would not take the
priority of topics, therefore they would carry out their hostile
role according to a scheme designed to attach Iraq and the Arab
Nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
