<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM to Visit S. Africa Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is to visit South Africa Wednesday in a bid to promote relations between
the two countries, the Sunday Independent, a newspaper published here
reported.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day visit, Blair will have talks with South African
leaders focusing on building new relations which began after South Africa's
1994
elections. He is also expected to announce British assistance for South
Africa's election to be held in May.
</P>
<P>
Blair's visit follows South African President Nelson Mandela's trip to
Britain in July last year and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's meeting with
Blair at Downing Street in November.
</P>
<P>
It will also mark the second meeting of Britain-South Africa Bilateral
Forum, a body established in July last year to enhance existing trade,
development and investment relationships.
</P>
<P>
Trade ties between South Africa and Britain are certain to receive a
significant fillip this year as three of the seven billion-U.S. Dollar
defense contracts approved recently by the South African cabinet were won
by Britain.
</P>
<P>
Counter trade deals will see 5.7 billion U.S. Dollars worth of
bilateral trade in 1997 (up by 28 percent from 1996) surge this year,
according to South African trade officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
