<HEADLINE> U.N. Mission to Stop Flights into C. Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 3 (XInhua) -- The United Nations observer mission in
Angola said Sunday it will stop chartering planes including those
delivering humanitarian aid to central Angola where fighting are still
going on.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at a time when a U.N. C-130 transport plane
was shot down Saturday in central Angola, bringing the number of planes
downed in the same area to two in eight days.
</P>
<P>
A press communique by the U.N. mission said the second plane crashed in
central Angola, about 80 km northwest of Huambo city, capital of Huambo
Province, where the government army was still fighting with the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) .
</P>
<P>
U.N. mission chief Issa Diallo confirmed that all U.N. flights in Angola
now had been suspended.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said he was outraged that a second U.N.
-chartered aircraft was shot down in Angola over UNITA held territory
within eight days.
</P>
<P>
The plane which was rented from South Africa's Transafrik corporation
took off from
Huambo airport at 15:00 pm Saturday and was heading for the capital Luanda.
 There were eight people aboard, four of them were U.N. officials while the
rest were the crew members.
</P>
<P>
On December 26 of last year, a U.N. C-130 transport plane was downed
near Huambo city. So far, no one knows if there is any survivor among the
ten on board the plane or the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has called on the Angolan government and the UNITA to
offer their cooperation so as to enter the site. Diallo said the U.N. was
trying to obtain government and UNITA assistance in the search and rescue
operations.
</P>
<P>
The downing of the two U.N. planes comes as Angola's peace accord
unravels and the oil- and diamond-rich southern African country resumes its
civil war which started with independence from Portugal in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
