<HEADLINE> Egypt Says Arab Consultations Underway for Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Sunday that consultations are underway among Arab
countries on the planned Arab foreign ministers meeting scheduled
for later this month.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that he and a number of Arab foreign
ministers held a meeting in Egypt Saturday on the issue. He did
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Middle East News Agency quoted well-informed sources as
saying that Moussa and his counterparts of Oman, Saudi Arabia,
Syria and Yemen met in the Red Sea resort of Hurghada, 400
kilometers southeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The five-way meeting was aimed at reaching a general agreement
among Arab countries on issues to be raised at the upcoming
foreign ministers meeting, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that intensive discussions of the kind will
continue in the upcoming stage to seek good preparations for the
meeting and examine the current situation in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries planned initially to hold a foreign ministers
meeting to discuss a Yemeni call for an emergency Arab summit on
the Iraqi issue after the recent U.S.-Britain military strikes on
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Requested by Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and other Gulf countries,
Arab states agreed last Monday to put off the proposed meeting to
January 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
