<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Claims of Stalling Peace in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa Sunday denied claims by
Zimbabwean press that it was stalling efforts to end fighting in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The South African Foreign Affairs Department said in a statement
it would do nothing that would encourage the forces in conflict which might
have any effect of undermining the peace process in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
"In so doing the government has been acutely aware that any delay in
bringing about a negotiated solution to the conflict could have disastrous
consequences, not only for the economic reconstruction and development of
the DRC, but for the well-being of all the inhabitants of our continent,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the Congolese rebel forces were an important element
which
could not be excluded from the cease-fire if an end to the hostilities was
to be ensured.
</P>
<P>
"This, however, does not amount to elevating rebels to heads of state,
according them VIP treatment, or undermining the sovereignty of the DRC
government as alleged in the Zimbabwean press," it added.
</P>
<P>
The South African government remained committed in assisting all
international efforts aimed at bringing lasting peace in Congo (K) at the
earliest possible moment.
</P>
<P>
"Only all-inclusive negotiations involving all parties to the conflict
can ensure lasting peace in the DRC," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in Congo (K) erupted in August last year when rebels,
being
supported by neighboring Rwanda and Uganda, tried to topple the government
headed by President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
South African leaders, together with their African counterparts, have
been trying to mediate between the warring sides, but no efficient results
have
been achieved yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
