<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Heavy rains over last week in Morocco raised
expectations that the country's grain output would be higher this
season.
</P>
<P>
After this season's profuse rains, the farm land area is
expected to expand from the current 7.5 million acres to 10
million acres.
</P>
<P>
It was predicted that Morocco's 1998 to 1999 harvest would
decrease to 4 million tonnes from 6.35 million tonnes last season
due to the dry weather.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian government earmarked 4 billion pounds
(1.2 billion U.S. dollars) of loans to farmers at a 10 percent
interest rate over 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Khidre, president of the Credit and Agricultural
Development Bank said in a statement that the loans come within
the new facilities of lending offered by the bank's branches
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The move is seen as being in favor of animal husbandry, fishing
and poultry entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanians were caught by an unexpected shortage of
liquefied gas though officials with the Jordan Petroleum Refinery
Company are trying their best to meet the public demand.
</P>
<P>
Relief to the situation is expected Wednesday when 40,000
tonnes of liquefied gas, ordered from Greece, arrives at the
Aqaba harbor in southern Jordan, Minister of Energy Hani Mulki
was quoted as saying by the national daily Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied rumors that liquefied gas supplies from
Iraq, the only oil and natural gas source of the kingdom
following the 1991 Gulf War, was affected by the U.S.-British air
attack on Iraq in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan does not face a problem with Iraq concerning gas and
Iraqi officials are very understanding of Jordan`s situation", the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Jordan Petroleum Refinery Company just
received 37,000 tonnes of liquefied gas from Iraq, and employees
at gas stations are working 24 hours a day to meet the need of
some desperate Jordanians who are queuing up outside gas stations
with empty cylinders in the freezing weather.
</P>
<P>
The company had attributed the sudden shortage of liquefied
gas to the current cold wave sweeping the kingdom, where daily
consumption of liquefied gas soared to 1,250 tonnes a day from 500
to 550 tonnes a day under normal circumstances.




03/01/99 18:33 GMT

NNNN
02:38 02:38 g # PAB
</P>
