<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Won't Militarily Intervene Congo Conflicts: Salim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Africa Unity
(OAU) Sunday ruled out the possibility of using military forces to end
conflicts in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim made the remarks
here when interviewed by the Dar es Salaam Television (DTV) that use of
military force in the central African nation will flare up the war
uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
He said the only lasting solution to the conflicts in DRC is to broaden
a political ground where every interested party in the conflicts could be
given a chance to participate in promoting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Relevant parties should be given chances to express their security
concerns, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if OAU principle on non-intervention in sovereign states could be
written off from the OAU charter to make way for countries to intervene in
situation like that of the DRC, Salim said that could be more dangerous to
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said the provision is a cornerstone of OAU, and scrapping it from
the OAU charter would mean allowing big powers to intervene in small
nations'
affairs at will.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief, however, noted that maintenance of the principle is not
a certificate of acceptability for rulers in some African countries who
would do whatever they like.
</P>
<P>
Questioned about how long OAU should wait for negotiations on the DRC
conflicts to bear fruits, Salim said he hoped the current efforts made by
OAU would gear up the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Salim said although he wished peace could prevail in the vast central
African country, peace might be achieved longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on human rights violation in the continent, the
OAU chief said the situation of human rights agenda in the continent is
gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
"There is a big change. The press is now dynamic and independent and
that there is a vivid sensitization of people to their human rights," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the resolution to introduce a human rights court in Africa
passed by OAU was yet another example of Africa's commitment to observance
of human rights.
</P>
<P>
On whether OAU was financially sound to set up the court, Salim said
Africa could not make financial constraints an excuse for not starting the
important court.
</P>
<P>
Some countries in Africa have shown an interest in instituting the
court and some of them have even expressed desires to foot initial bills,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
