<HEADLINE> Russia Urges U.N. to Take Measures against UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia Foreign Ministry Sunday in
a statement strongly condemned Angola's UNITA guerilla group for
shooting down another U.N. plane in the Angolan skies on Sunday,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Russian side insistently demands that the United Nations
immediately react to these outrageous actions of UNITA. The
Security Council must use against this organization resolute and
utterly rigorous measures allowed by the U.N. Charter," the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time in the last few days that UNITA (the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola), shot down a
U.N. plane over Angola.
</P>
<P>
"This terrorist act is particularly outrageous because only two
days have passed since the U.N. Security Council demanded that the
UNITA leader, Jonas Savimbi, make an immediate investigation into
an incident in which a U.N. aeroplane was shot down in December
and take urgent measures to find out what had happened to the crew
and passengers of the plane, who included two Russian citizens,"
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Six civilian aeroplanes have lately been shot down over the
territory controlled by UNITA. It, the ministry said, "is evidence
that this antigovernment group is in effect pursuing a systematic
line against the entire international community."
</P>
<P>
The victims are "citizens of various countries, including
Russia, and it is still unknown what has happened to them."
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian Foreign Ministry, there had been no
Russians aboard the craft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
