<HEADLINE> Chiluba Calls for More African-American Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambian president Frederick Chiluba Sunday
called on African-American investors to help their African brothers and
sisters by investing more in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when Cyrhia Mckinney, U.S. congress woman from the
city of Atlanta, paid a courtesy call on him.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Zambia needs investment from African-Americans in
order to cement the relationship which already exists between Zambia and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Zambia is a heaven of peace and tranquility as no
investor will take his investment in chaos.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has reached a critical point in the economy after the
liberalization, and has experienced a lot of retrenchments because the new
owners of companies want to make them more viable.
</P>
<P>
The privatization, he said, has caused some social and political
problems in his country and reduced living standard of some people.
</P>
<P>
Mckinney told Chiluba that before coming to Zambia she held discussions
with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Africa and Zambia in particular.
</P>
<P>
"I agree with President Clinton that the United States policy in Africa
has not been as it should be," she said.
</P>
<P>
She called for more support to Zambia from the the U.S. government,
adding that Zambia should be supported for its efforts in
democratization.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants partnership with Africa based on dignity and
cooperation and improved relations with Africa through business ties, she
noted.
</P>
<P>
Mckinney also praised Zambia for its peace efforts in the war-torn
Democratic Republic of Congo and Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
