<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICRC Meeting on POWs Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee
of the Red Cross (ICRC) said Sunday that an ICRC sub-committee
meeting to discuss the issue of Kuwaiti and third country's
prisoners of war (POWs) was indefinitely postponed because the
Iraqis refused to show up.
</P>
<P>
Bernard Pfefferle, regional delegate of the ICRC, said the
meeting of the technical sub-committee, which was scheduled to be
held Monday on the Kuwaiti side of the border with Iraq, would not
take place, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting has been indefinitely put off," Pfefferle said.
</P>
<P>
He said the "Iraqi authorities has informed the ICRC that the
Iraqi delegation will not be participating in the 37th session of
the technical sub-committee."
</P>
<P>
"The ICRC was in the process of clarifying the reason of such
non-participation," Pfefferle said.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC-sponsored sub-committee is composed of Iraq on one
side, the United States, Britain, France, Saudi Arabia and Kuwait
on the other.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait insisted that Iraq still holds more than 600 Kuwaiti
and third country's detainees since the end of the 1990 Gulf
War. But Baghdad has repeatedly denied that it held any POWs of
any country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
