<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Forces Me Out: Tanzanian Police Boss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Police Boss Cossy Odomel, who
has announced his plan to resign soon, said that he was forced by
President Yoweri Museveni to step down.
</P>
<P>
He made this remarks Saturday when interviewed by the New Vision
newspaper, which was published by the newspaper Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Odomel said he was directed to resign from the top police post by the
appointing authority on the top of which is the president.
</P>
<P>
Hel did not specify the reasons for the directive although there is
speculation that the president acted on a corruption probe report about him.
</P>
<P>
Police Commander of Kampala Region Extra, Benjamin Namanya told Xinhua
Sunday morning in a telephone interview that he was greatly shocked at the
police boss' announcement at the party hosted Friday here to entertain
senior police commanders.
</P>
<P>
"I did not expect that at the time. Odomel just said he would quit his
job and live a civilian life. He did not say anything about what he would
do after resigning," Namanya said.
</P>
<P>
The New Vision report said the police boss is running businesses which
are supplying items to the police force.
</P>
<P>
He is alleged to have been a signatory to all payments and his
companies were always paid earlier than other suppliers.
</P>
<P>
The Inspector General of Government has since October 1998 been probing
Odomel's alleged amassing of wealth estimated at two billion shillings (two
million U.S. Dollars), but he said he had not seen any report on alleged
abuse of office.
</P>
<P>
This is shocking news to Ugandans following exposure of big scandals in
the privatization of parastatals in which one minister has resigned and
another is likely to face censure from the Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
