<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, January 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has
refused to meet with Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon during
his upcoming visit to the United States, English-language paper
the Jerusalem Post reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is scheduled to travel to New York this week to attend
a convention of Israeli consuls-general, and efforts were made to
arrange a meeting with Albright during his stay.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted U.S. sources as saying that Sharon wanted to
discuss final status topics with his U.S. counterpart, but his
request was rejected. He was told that there was no reason to
talk about final status matters while Israel refused to implement
even the interim agreements. (BC-Israel-US-Sharon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- One of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
former aides launched a new immigrant party Sunday to compete in
the upcoming elections, posing a threat to the largest existing
immigrant party.
</P>
<P>
Avigdor Lieberman, Netanyahu's former director-general,
announced at a news conference the establishment of Yisrael
Beiteinu, or Israel Is Our Home, a right-wing immigrants' party
with a platform focusing on social justice.
</P>
<P>
His party is expected to split the votes of Yisrael Baaliya, a
party representing immigrants from former Soviet Union and headed
by Trade and Industry Minister Natan Sharansky.
(BC-Israel-elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Sunday denied a Japanese television report
that Tehran had purchased ballistic missiles from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi termed the
report as "unfounded," and said the Islamic Republic of Iran has
announced time and again that it has no missile cooperation with
other countries, including the DPRK, the Islamic Republic News
Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The Japan broadcasting corporation (NHK) reported on Saturday
that the DPRK has built 30 of its first-generation ballistic
Rodong missiles and exported some of them to Iran and Pakistan.
(BC-Iran-Denial-Missile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Seven people, including a Lebanese mother and her
four daughters, were wounded on Sunday in Israeli air raids on
Lebanon's eastern Bekaa Valley, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted security sources as saying that Israeli jets
fired two air-to-surface missiles at a radio station run by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, near the country's
ancient Roman city of Baalbek in Bekaa.
</P>
<P>
The group's Voice of the Oppressed radio station, whose
transmitter was damaged during the air attack, went off the air,
the sources said. (BC-Lebanon-Israel-Wounded)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on Sunday chaired the
first cabinet session of this year on Sunday to discuss his
government's position toward the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Saddam accused the U.S. of spreading false information to "calm
the Arab public opinion rejective of such imperialistic
Anglo-American onslaught on Iraq."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the U.S. allegation that it did not attack
Iraqi sites first, but the Iraqi air defense force started firing
at U.S. planes, according to the Iraqi News Agency (INA).
(BC-Iraq-Cabinet Meeting)


03/01/99 20:58 GMT

NNNN
05:02 05:03 g # PAB
</P>
