<HEADLINE> Vietnam Attracts Over 4 Bln Dollars of Foreign Investment in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 260 foreign-invested
projects with combined capital of 4.058 billion U.S. dollars were
granted licenses in Vietnam in 1998, Vietnam news agency reported
Monday, quoting the Ministry of Planning and Investment (MPI).
</P>
<P>
In addition, 133 on-going projects were permitted to increase
their investment capital by 769 million U.S. dollars, bringing the
country's total investment capital licensed last year to over 4.8
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of projects and the amount of foreign
investment capital in Vietnam in 1998 dropped by 21.5 percent and
10.1 percent respectively compared to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Among 29 countries and regions investing in Vietnam last year,
Russia ranked first in terms of investment capital with 2 billion
dollars, followed by Singapore, which registered 893 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sectors that attracted large foreign investment in 1998
included the oil and gas industry with four projects worth 1.358
billion dollars, hotel and tourism with six projects capitalized
at 810.4 million dollars, heavy industry with 40 projects valued
at 551.3 million dollars, transport, communications and post with
12 projects worth 366.2 million dollars, and light industry with
54 projects worth 202.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Operating foreign-invested projects' total turnover last year
reached 3 billion dollars, a 27.6 percent increase over 1997, and
their export value was 2 billion dollars, a year-on-year rise of
11.7 percent. These projects created 269,500 jobs and contributed
320 million dollars to the state budget, a growth of 1.6 percent
over 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
