<HEADLINE> Security Council to Meet on Plane Crash in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
is expected to meet behind closed doors at 5:00 p.m. EST Monday to
discuss two U.N. planes downed in Angola in eight days, U.N.
officials announced.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan is scheduled to brief the
15-nation council on what is going on in Angola, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The council's closed-door meeting came after the rebel National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) was reported to
shoot down a U.N.-chartered cargo plane Saturday, the second
United Nations plane apparently attacked in Angola's central
highland war zone in eight days.
</P>
<P>
The C-130 aircraft, with eight people aboard, was hit by
anti-aircraft fire 20 minutes after it took off from the city of
Huambo, about 480 kilometers southeast of the Angolan capital of
Luanda.
</P>
<P>
However, UNITA denied that it downed the plane.
</P>
<P>
The plane that crashed Saturday was carrying U.N. equipment out
of Huambo. Last week, the United Nations evacuated dozens of staff
members from the city after it was briefly shelled by the
advancing rebels.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has condemned the rebels for failing
to help the United Nations determine the fate of crash victims and
has signaled it may take unspecified action against UNITA.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Annan, who said he was "outraged" by the
accidents, reiterated the appeals for the Angolan government and
rebels to assist in rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
"All threats to U.N. personnel -- in the air and on the ground
-- must cease immediately," Annan said in a statement, urging both
sides to observe an immediate cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
UNITA stymied the implementation of the 1994 peace pact by
refusing to surrender the control of its central highland
strongholds and by keeping a 30,000-strong army hidden in the
bush.
</P>
<P>
The accord unraveled in December when government troops tried
to take the strongholds by force and were beaten back. Recent
battles have focused around Huambo, the provincial capital which
is 150 kilometers away from the crash site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
