<HEADLINE> Nigeria Deploys More Troops in Niger Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has deployed more
troops in the oil-producing Niger Delta areas where youth protests are
threatening oil production, media reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Bayelsa were quoted as saying that many military check-
points had been installed while armored personnel carriers patrolled
Bayelsa State.
</P>
<P>
Sources in Yenagoa, capital of Bayelsa State, said that the government
deployed more troops in Niger Delta Sunday and two naval vessels crossed
into the waters of the area at the weekend with combat ready personnel on
board.
</P>
<P>
A source said that 10 military tanks and several police armored
personnel carriers had been moved in to help end the four-day crisis which
had claimed at least 20 lives.
</P>
<P>
"A further reinforcement of troops is being expected from the army
barracks in Emele, Port Harcourt," the source added.
</P>
<P>
The Bayelsa State police commissioner, Nahum Eli, said at the weekend
that the state police command had closed two police stations to avoid an
imminent violent clash between the police and youths in the state,
according to a Daily Times report Monday.
</P>
<P>
Violence broke out in the area last Wednesday following the expiration
of December 30 ultimatum given to the Nigerian government by the Ijaw
youths.
</P>
<P>
Bayelsa State Administrator Paul Obi declared a state of
emergency in the state following three people were killed by government
troops during a confrontation on December 30.
</P>
<P>
The youth in Bayelsa State held a meeting on December 11 and issued the
"Kaiama Declaration" , demanding the withdrawal of security force sent to
protect oil installations in the area and the stoppage of oil exploration
and exploitation activities by oil companies until the ownership and
control of the coast oil deposits is determined.  
</P>
</TEXT>
