<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Iran Want to Maintain Tradition of Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Iran have agreed
on the need to maintain the tradition of cooperation in areas of
mutual interest including economic, commercial, technical,
scientific and cultural fields, the Foreign Office here said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also agreed to work together for the
restoration of peace and stability in Afghanistan, said a press
release by the Foreign Office said in a press release on Foreign
Secretary Shamshad Ahmed's three-day visit to Iran from January
2-4.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Shamshad and Iranian officials in Tehran "led
to a better understanding of each other's point of view and
concerns on the major issues," it said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held two rounds of extensive discussions covering
the entire range of Pakistan-Iran relations as well as regional
issues of mutual interest with particular focus on Afghanistan,
the Kashmir issue and peace and security in South Asia, it said.
</P>
<P>
A detailed exchange of views was held on the situation in
Afghanistan, the release said. "Both sides reiterated their common
commitment to the early restoration of peace and stability in
Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
"They also supported the formation of a broad-based multiethnic
government through an indigenous process", said the release.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, it was also decided that the 11th meeting of
the Pakistan-Iran Joint Ministerial Commission will be convened in
Islamabad in the near future, and meetings of other joint
commissions and committees will be held in the coming months, it
added.
</P>
<P>
On the Kashmir issue, the release said the Iranian side
reiterated its traditional support to the Kashmir cause and called
for an early peaceful settlement of the issue in accordance with
the U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
