<HEADLINE> HK's Bank of East Asia Celebrates 80th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of East Asia, the
largest independent Chinese bank in Hong Kong, held a ceremony
here Monday to celebrate its 80th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, and other government officials, leading
business figures and customers of the bank attended the reception.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the event, David Li, chairman and chief executive of
the bank, said the history of the bank is a success story. "Not
only the success of one company, but the success of a whole city
and its people," Li added.
</P>
<P>
"In the 80 years since it opened its doors, the bank has been
proud to support enterprising people and growing businesses
locally and around the world."
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1918, the bank has developed extensive overseas
network and has a total of 139 branches and representative
offices, with over 4,000 staff, around the world.
</P>
<P>
With 105 branches, it is the largest locally owned bank in Hong
Kong. The bank has 17 outlets in major cities in China's mainland
and has recently become one of the first overseas banks to win
approval to operate Reminbi services in both Shenzhen and
Shanghai, a press release from the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Together with its subsidiaries and associated companies, it is
a fully integrated provider of financial services spanning retail
and wholesale banking, asset management, stockbroking, property
agency services, consulting and insurance, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
