<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Amend Immigration Act to Check Illegal Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will further amend
the Immigration Act 1956/1963 to check illegal entry, and a bill
to this effect is likely to be tabled in Parliament in March,
Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Amendments to the Immigration Act would stipulate that no
occupier of a work place shall permit any illegal immigrant or
foreign national without a valid work pass to enter or remain at
the work place, Tajol said, the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Tajol said that with the new provisions the owner would be held
fully responsible if any illegal immigrant was detained in his
premises or work place, construction site or rented houses.
</P>
<P>
The amendments to the Act would also provide for the
admissibility of a sworn statement by the witness without the
witness being present in person.
</P>
<P>
"If Parliament approves the Bill, it will be enforced in the
middle of this year," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
There are estimated 2 million foreign workers in Malaysia,
mostly from Indonesia, the Philippines and Bangladesh, and among
them almost half are illegal.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia launched a foreign national regularization program
last year for the first time, and a total of 413,000 foreigners
mostly from Indonesia and the Philippines were registered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
