<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Stock Trade up by 78% in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Stock Exchange recorded a 78
percent increase in trade volume in 1998, despite a plunge for its All
Share Index for the second consecutive year, the Punch newspaper said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said about 2.11 billion shares changed hands in 1998 in the
stock market, compared with 1.3 billion shares in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the value of all shares traded increased from 11.9 billion
Naira (138 million U.S. Dollars) to 14.6 billion Naira (170 million dollars)
.
</P>
<P>
Stockbrokers attributed the improved activities to the introduction of
the Central Securities Clearing System which has reduced the transaction
period.
</P>
<P>
Other factors that boosted the turnover in 1998 are the introduction of
trading in rights and the United Bank for Africa Global Depository Receipts
(GDR).
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the GDR has attracted voluminous transactions by
foreign investors, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
