<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Urges African Countries to Fight HIV/AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 ADDIS ABABA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) Monday called on all African heads of state and government to
formulate a plan of action to fight the
AIDS disease.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Ambassador Ahmed Haggag, OAU Assistant Secretary
General, at the opening session of a two-day colloquium on the challenge
of HIV/AIDS in Africa, which was held at the Africa Hall here.
</P>
<P>
Haggag stressed that multi-sectoral committee should be set up in each
member state with national budgetary allocations in order to effectively
coordinate all programs and activities aimed at implementing the OAU Dakar
(1992) and Tunis (1994) declarations on HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that programs to control further spread of HIV and to
take care of those affected by AIDS should be country-driven rather than
donor-driven.
</P>
<P>
"Governments should encourage the mass media, schools and religiours
leaders to provide free information against HIV/AIDS to all communities
especially in rural areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session, Klint Nyamur Yekung'e, the Joint
United Nations
programs on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) country program adviser, said Monday that
out of a total of 5.8 million who acquired the infection in 1998 worldwide,
4.0 million live in Africa south of Sahara.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the epidemic began, 34 million Africans have been
infected, and almost 12 million of them have died.
</P>
<P>
 The two-day meeting is organized by the Mother and Child African
Relief Organization, which is a non-governmental organization in special
consultative status with the Economic and Social Council of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, Africa will be confronted with 20 million of her
children infected by HIV, according to the Mother and Child African Relief
Organization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
