<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Prepared to Face Widening Trade Deficit:Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government was
prepared to face the widening trade deficit which had reached 6.7
billion U.S. dollars during April-November last year, Finance
Minister Yashwant Sinha said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen the trend so far," Sinha told reporters, adding
that "We are prepared ourselves" for a widened trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
However, Sinha refused to specify any figure concerning the
trade imbalance at the year-end, saying he would not hazard a
guess against various estimates that had come so far.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit for the first eight months of the current
fiscal year which began on April 1, 1998 was officially estimated
at 6.7 billion U.S. dollars, which is more than double that of 3.3
billion U.S. dollars in the previous corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest data, India's exports during the
eight-month period were estimated at 21.5 billion U.S. dollars, or
3.97 percent less than 22.36 billion U.S. dollars registered in
April-November 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports were put at 28.2 billion U.S. dollars, 9.5 percent
higher than 25.7 billion U.S. dollars in the same period 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the increasing gold import was the main reason for the
widening trade deficit and the government was looking ways to curb
it.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the fiscal deficit was under pressure and said
he was trying to keep it as close to the budget estimate of 5.6
percent of the Gross Domestic Product as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
