<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Property Value Goes up in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 LUSAKA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Over estimation of property value and
the pegging of property rentals to the U.S. Dollar has resulted in an
average of
30 percent increase in property values in 1998 particularly in the capital
city of Lusaka, Times of Zambia reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a real property consultant as saying that because
of the slumping property market and the construction industry as well as a
40
percent depreciation of the country's currency Kwacha in the year, most
landlords have overestimated the value of their properties without
consulting qualified valuation surveyors.
</P>
<P>
 Managing partner of Bitrust Real Estate Consult, Holand Mulenga said
because of this trend tenacy defaults on rental payment increased by a
wide margin during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Giving a preview of the property market in Zambia, he said
tire dollarization of property rentals by most landlords in the country is
due to the constant fall of the Kwacha and the desire by most property
owners to stabilize their investment.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that charging rent in Dollars is not a fool proof
hedge
against fluctuating investment returns on property.
</P>
<P>
"Tenants also derive their incomes from the same economically weak
investment environment, and 90 percent of potential customers earn their
incomes in Kwacha and so will have the same difficulties in raising the
dollar rental demands,"he said.
</P>
<P>
 The trend in 1998 saw most property owners concentrating on the drive
for maximum rental income returns without commensurate rise in the level of
maintenance of property, he said,
</P>
<P>
 Mulenga noted that property owners in Zambia should not expect rentals
to
keep rising in the new year due to a fall in effective demand in real
property.
</P>
<P>
 He urged the property owners to increase investment in 1999 in
property maintenance to achieve a positive growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
