<HEADLINE> China Lists Licensed Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China has sharply reduced the
number of licensed export commodities in an effort to boost
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC)
recently announced that 58 export products, or half the 115
products in 1998, will be subject to licensing administration
during 1999. In addition, the number of commodity codes will be
reduced from 707 to 395.
</P>
<P>
The new list consists of commodities exported to certain
countries and regions, as well as fresh crab, livestock and
poultry exports to Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Designated departments will license part of the listed
commodities for entry through designated customs areas.
</P>
<P>
A MOFTEC official noted that the move is a major part of
China's reform on administration of exports during 1999. He said
the move will help increase China's exports, streamline
application procedure and standardize order in the export
sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
