<TEXT>

<P>
LUANDA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Angola yielded two million karats of
diamond
 in 1998, with a value of 450 million U.S. Dollars, the major source of
income for the mineral sector, the Ministry of Geology and Mines revealed
in a
document.
 The document available here Monday said that the figure represents a 65
percent
growth over 1997, when Angola produced 1.314 million karats of diamond, with
a value of 350 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the diamond sector is regaining its vigor from
decline
and standstill for many years, the ministry document said.
</P>
<P>
 Angola had registered its record high diamond production of 2.41
million karats,
ranking the fourth in the world diamond-producing nations, but its
production saw
a sharp decline in the decades of civil war.
</P>
<P>
 The ministry is implementing its plans to revitalize the
diamond industry and absorb more foreign investment, so as to make the
industry contribute more to the restoration of the national economy, the
document said.
</P>
<P>
 The ministry is still concerned over the re-start of military
conflicts in
some parts of the country, which may hinder the plans implementation and
the inflow of investment from abroad, it said.
</P>
<P>
 It said that about half of the diamonds produced in 1998 are still in
the
hands of smuggler groups, including the rebel National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) . 
</P>
