<HEADLINE> Thailand Witnesses First Day of Euro Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The euro began its first day of
trading in Thailand on Monday but had little impact on markets
here or in the rest of the region, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
The unit was selling at 42.58-84 Thai baht in early trade and
the buying of euro here was very light, according to the dealers.
</P>
<P>
Because of the strength of the European unit, the baht was
trading stronger at 36.27-34 to the U.S. dollar, compared to
36.60-65 on the last day of trade in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the Japanese yen might be pushed back to third
position as the currency of choice with respect to the euro's
arrival.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese have been pushing the yen aggressively as an
alternative to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Although the trade of euro was light, traders would be watching
the unit closely.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's central bank said it would change a chunk of its
foreign exchange reserves into the new Europe currency.
</P>
<P>
"The central bank here will gradually convert its assets in
Deutsch marks, French francs and other European currencies into
the euro," said Assistant Bank of Thailand governor Kiatisak
Meecharoen.
</P>
<P>
"Those holdings together account for about 10 percent of
foreign currency holdings," he said.
</P>
<P>
Total Thai foreign exchange reserves currently stand at 30
billion dollars, according to official figures. 
</P>
