<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Hit by Textile Smugglers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 4 (Xinhua) - Tanzania suffers a loss of billions
of Tanzanian Shillings (one U.S. Dollar equals to 680 Shillings) annually
in
revenue from textile smuggling, a national newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Mail newspaper quoted a report by the Textile Manufacturers
Association of Tanzania (TMAT) as saying that tax evasion and smuggling
have been the major cause leading to a total collapse of the domestic
textile sector.
</P>
<P>
The report, addressed to the government last week, disclosed the
techniques used by the textile importers to evade taxes.
</P>
<P>
The TMAT said that under the transit route technique most of the Duty
Entitlement Pass Book documents indicate that the consignments originate
from Dubai, the United Arab Emirates, and the destination port usually is
Zanzibar or Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
It elaborates that on receiving the merchandise mostly from India, the
agents in Dubai would re-ship the cargo to countries neighboring Tanzania
via Dar es Salaam Port.
</P>
<P>
"The goods would then be falsely declared at Dar es Salaam port and
cleared by the use of transit entries. The papers would then be taken to
the border entry points for stamping by Tanzania Revenue Authority
officials there," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the transit entry documents were then brought back to
Customs Department in Dar es Salaam for bond cancellation, while the goods
found their way into the local market virtually free of tax.
</P>
<P>
"Under this technique the Exchequer is totally denied of any revenue
and the domestic industry virtually robbed of its legitimate market share. "
</P>
<P>
Besides the transit route technique, textile importers have evaded tax
by importing goods into the Mainland through Zanzibar by under declaration
of the quantity of the goods and their price value.
</P>
<P>
"The Mombasa-Sirari-Mwanza and Mombasa-Kisumu-Mwanza routes have also
been used to evade tax by textile importers," the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
