<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bjorkman Beats Gambill in Hopman Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two teams split the singles matches, but Bjorkman and
teammate Asa Carlsson were too strong in the mixed doubles,
winning in straight sets to clinch the tie, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Bjorkman is aiming to rejuventate his singles career this
year, having slipped to No. 24 in the rankings after reaching a
high of four in 1997, and looked in great touch with the
Australia Open less than a month away.
</P>
<P>
He was far too strong for American Jan-Michael Gambill, ranked
38th in the world, in the singles, winning 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Bjorkman then carried that form through to the mixed doubles,
controlling play and covering plenty of court to win 7-6 (7-2)
6-4.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Lindsay Davenport had earlier got the Americans
off to a flying start by downing Carlsson 6-2, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Bjorkman, 26, said he had been having troubles with his right
hamstring in recent weeks and hadn't expected to find touch so
quickly.
</P>
<P>
"I even surprised myself," he said."I played really well in
singles and mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
"It's a great way to start 1999."
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old American didn't help his cause with five
double faults and didn't have a break point in either set.
</P>
<P>
The mixed doubles result was a great relief to Carlsson, who
hadn't won a match in her two previous visits to Perth, having
lost four doubles matches and four singles matches.
</P>
<P>
She earlier lost her fifth singles match when Davenport gave
the United States a perfect start, overpowering the 92nd ranked
Carlsson in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
Davenport said she was delighted with the way she hit the ball
in her first match for six weeks, but commended the Swedes for
their performance in the mixed doubles.
</P>
<P>
The United States now face Switzerland in their next Group B
match, while Sweden meets the Slovak Republic.
</P>
<P>
The late match tonight is between France and Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
