<HEADLINE> New Group Formed in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PESHAWAR, Pakistan, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Afghan
president Sibghatullah Mujaddedi and chief of National Islamic
Front of Afghanistan (NIFA) Pir Syed Gillani have formed a new
group with the aim of achieving an immediate cease-fire and
restoring peace to their war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here Monday at the residence of
Mujaddedi, they announced the formation of "Associated for Peace
and National Unity in Afghanistan, aimed at bringing peace in
Afghanistan and halting the on-going war through rapprochement
among the warring Afghan factions.
</P>
<P>
"Our effort has been supported by a number of Afghan
organizations, political and religious groups, important
personalities, intellectuals and others," they claimed, adding:
"We have also been assured of cooperation by these people."
</P>
<P>
Mujaddedi said that since the troops of the former Soviet Union
withdrew from Afghanistan, the Afghans have not seen calm yet in
their country.
</P>
<P>
"Ironically, this blood-letting continued in Afghanistan and if
a serious effort was not made to stop it, it seems to me that it
will devour generation after generation of our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The increasing agonies and torment faced by the Afghans in the
wake of war have compelled us to take a new initiative to create a
peaceful and a livable atmosphere in the war-torn country,"
Mujaddedi added.
</P>
<P>
Pir Gillani hoped that the Afghans will extend full support to
their efforts for peace. He said that despite being in control of
most of the Afghan territory by the Taliban, it is not possible
for them to provide basic needs to the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
Pir Gillani stressed the need for convening a Grand Girga
(assembly of people) of Afghans to decide the type of the future
system in Afghanistan. But Grand Girga cannot be held without
peace in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, Mujaddedi said they were committed to
making efforts for the peace and hoped that the Afghan nation will
support them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
