<HEADLINE> Overseas Capital Flows Into Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China has used overseas
funds of close to 4.7 billion US dollars for environmental
protection projects over the past three years, according to
today's China Economic Times.
</P>
<P>
The 4.7 billion dollars actually used by the end of last year
represented a four-fold rise on the total figure used during the
Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995).
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission had approved the use
of overseas funds totaling 2.3 billion US dollars for 21
environmental protection projects by the end of 1998, the third
year of the Ninth Five-Year Plan Period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
An additional 19 projects involving 2.4 billion dollars were
approved during the early stage of preparations, according to the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funds have been used for the construction of
environmental protection infrastructure, pollution control and
developing the industry.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the sector note that the use of overseas funds
has injected substantial capital into China's environmental
programs and has helped transform the industry into a new economic
growth area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
