<HEADLINE> China's Medical Experts Concerned at Growth of Sex Shops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Worried about the growing number
of sex shops, which are opening all over China, and their often
unprofessional practises, Chinese medical experts are calling for
a nationwide plan to bring order to the business.
</P>
<P>
There are no official statistics on the number of such shops
but they can now be found in cities and rural townships alike; in
the downtown areas of the bigger metropolises and in the
backstreets of remote counties.
</P>
<P>
China's huge 1.2 billion population has undoubtedly the
potential to become the world's largest market for sexually
related products.
</P>
<P>
But the absence of any national code of conduct or regulations
governing the burgeoning industry has resulted in chaos with
unlicensed sex shops opening up and many selling suspicious sex
aids.
</P>
<P>
"The fledgling sex health business, which can be a boon to
China in terms of population control, is doomed if such a trend is
left unchecked," cautioned Li Zeyou, a member of China's Sexuality
Society (CSS), which took part in a national medical seminar in
Hefei.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the government should make hospitals,
health rehabilitation centers and special hospitals for
sex-related problems the main suppliers of sex health products
such as condoms and birth control pills. It should also issue
business licenses to sex shops to standardize their activities.
</P>
<P>
"Even grocery stores can be found selling condoms and
contraceptive pills, with prices varying from one yuan (about 0.82
U.S. cents) to ten yuan (1.25 U.S. dollars) apiece." added Li.
</P>
<P>
The executive chairman of the Society, Cao Xinwu, said: "What
also upsets a lot of people is that some drug stores display big
posters of naked men and women with erotic captions."
</P>
<P>
He added people's attitudes toward sex have changed a lot in
the last dozen or so years and he believes proper guidance has
become imperative. He stressed that the CSS will make every
efforts to ensure sex shops become more professional.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Traded Actively in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The new currency, the euro, of the
European Union was actively traded in Bangladesh's local
inter-bank market on Monday, which ended with a strong note
against the local currency, the taka, the official BSS news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The taka was quoted at 58.95 against the euro at the close of
the trading, from 56.9 at the beginning of trading, the news
agency quoted dealers as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahmudur Rahman, assistant vice president of the Arab
Bangladesh Bank, said he was the first local dealer to make an
inter-bank deal on the euro with the Standard Chartered Bank
(SCB).
</P>
<P>
The SCB, which had the largest dealing in euros with local and
foreign commercial banks here, had quoted over 1 million U.S.
dollars of trading in the new currency.
</P>
<P>
The euro was officially introduced on January 1 this year, but
came to the world money market trading on Monday (January 4) after
the New Year holiday.
</P>
<P>
Demand for the euro was high because the euro zone represents
30 percent of the world trading community and nearly 45 percent of
exports from Bangladesh goes to the euro zone, the BSS said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Bank, the central bank, has issued instructions to
all commercial banks for smooth transaction of the new currency
and requested those facing difficulties in euro trading to contact
the bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, demand for the U.S. dollar remained steady at the
end of the trading and the greenback was quoted at 48.6500/48.6520
against the taka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
