<HEADLINE> VietCombank Sets Vietnam Dong-Euro Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Ho Chi Minh City branch of
VietCombank (Vietnam commercial bank) announced the Vietnamese
Dong (VND)-euro exchange rate over the weekend, Vietnam's English
daily the Saigon Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The purchasing price of Europe's new currency, which was
introduced on January 1, was set at 16,273 VND, and the selling
price, 16,339 VND.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's state bank, however, has yet to make any official
announcement although the international financial market has begun
to trade the euro.
</P>
<P>
Due to a lack of the VND-euro exchange rate set by the central
bank, the difference between the buying and selling prices of the
euro against the local currency quoted by VietCombank Ho Chi Minh
City was as high as VND 66.
</P>
<P>
Truong Van Phuoc, deputy director of VietCombank Ho Chi Minh
City, explained that his branch had allowed such a wide difference
because the dollar-euro exchange rate on the world market was
fluctuating all the time.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is hard for businesses to choose the euro for
payments.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has requested the government to allow banks to
settle payments in the euro.
</P>
<P>
EU (European Union) countries now account for 11 percent of
Vietnam's total foreign investment and 42 percent of official
development assistance (ODA).
</P>
<P>
Five of the 11 EU member countries are traditional business
partners of Vietnam. In 1997, Vietnam's exports to France, Italy
and Belgium were worth more than 1 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
