<HEADLINE> Former US Assistant Defense Secretary on East Asian Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Former United States Assistant
Defense Secretary Joseph Nye said here today that good relations
between China, the US and Japan is of great importance in
maintaining security in east Asia, and it is important they should
find ways to take part in ongoing multilateral discussions on such
issues.
</P>
<P>
Nye, who currently serves as the dean of the Kennedy School of
Government of Harvard University, warned during his current visit
to China that unfavorable elements still exist which could disrupt
the relative stability of east Asia.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the US position on the Taiwan issue remains
unchanged, recalling that during US President Bill Clinton's tour
of Shanghai last year he had stressed his observance of the
"one-China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also promised during his China trip not to support
independence for Taiwan, or for "two Chinas", or "one Taiwan, one
China", nor to support Taiwan's participation in any international
organization which only sovereign countries can join.
</P>
<P>
Nye, a consistent optimist over the development of Sino-US
relations, expressed his satisfaction over their progress.
</P>
<P>
He is currently leading a Kennedy School delegation to China to
mark the 2nd anniversary of the establishment of the Nina Kung
Project which helps sponsor exchanges between administrative and
army personnel in both countries. 
</P>
