<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Air Controllers Can Serve in Any Country: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian air traffic controllers are
qualified to serve anywhere in the world as their training is based on
international criteria.
</P>
<P>
National Airports Corporation (NAC)'s principal air traffic controller,
Bustin Mubita, said this in an interview with the newspaper Business Mail
in
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Monday quoted Mubita as saying that as a member of the
International Civil Aviation Association, Zambia has to comply with its
standards to maintain professionalism.
</P>
<P>
"Air traffic controlling is an international profession whose training
follows an international criteria, Zambia-trained controllers are of
international standard and can perform anywhere in the world," Mutiba said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that as a delicate profession, air traffic controllers have to
be well trained to enable them to become cautious in discharging their
duties.
</P>
<P>
 "Air traffic controllers must know what they are doing and what is at
stake. It is critical for them to avoid air traffic accidents and loss of
life. They must also ensure the safety of passengers in the air," Mubita
said.
</P>
<P>
 Mubita recently led a team of 10 Zambian air traffic controllers to
Zimbabwe where they helped their counterparts to man the airspace
following an industrial dispute in Zimbabwe.  
</P>
