<HEADLINE> Kampala-Entebbe Highway's Construction Resumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on the stalled Kampala-
Entebbe highway resumed Monday after the Ugandan government paid the 2.4
million U.S Dollars it owed to the contractors.
</P>
<P>
The New Vision, a daily newspaper published here, Monday quoted an
official in the Ministry of Works, Housing and Communications as saying
over the weekend that the money was remitted on December 22, 1998, to
Skanska Jensen, one of the joint venture contractors working on the road.
</P>
<P>
Workers of the company grounded their tools early last month,
demanding
payment from the government before resuming work. The other contractor is
the Italian Sterling International.
</P>
<P>
The two companies were contracted to expand the five-kilometer-long
stretch from Kibuye roundabout to Zana into a dual carriage way at a cost
of 4.6 million U.S. Dollars.  
</P>
