<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Sharemarket Rings in New Year With Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
began the new year by closing higher Monday, with major
telecommunications stocks continuing to strengthen.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index rose 19.2 points to 2,832.6 despite a
flat resources sector.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a carryover of momentum and sentiment from the
last week of our market," Stuart Smith from Henderson Charlton
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
"That activity in the last week or so was the unwinding of
arbitrage positions (between the physical and futures markets) so
I would expect things to lighten off," he said.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index improved 40.7 points to 5,100.8, with
gains in telecommunications stocks offsetting late losses in major
banks.
</P>
<P>
Cable and Wireless Optus rose 13 cents after its market
weighting for index calculation increased to 50 percent of its
capitalization from the previous 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
Telstra shares climbed 19 cents, as investors continued to be
attracted to the certainty of earnings of the two
telecommunications majors.
</P>
<P>
Insurance major AMP rose 23.5 cents after its market weighting
moved to full capitalization from 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the major banks, Commonwealth dropped 26.3 cents and
Westpac fell 14.5 cents while National Australia Bank closed 5.9
cents higher and ANZ was 8 cents better.
</P>
<P>
Global media group News Corp. was one of the strongest blue
chips, with the ordinary shares up 22 cents and the preferred
scrip 19 cents higher.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index edged down 0.3 points to 974.4.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto shares fell 27.5 cents after announcing it had lifted
its stake in Comalco above 70 percent through on-market buys.
</P>
<P>
BHP rose 11.1 cents while North dropped 12 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index climbed 13.8 cents to 1,123.1.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion closed in Sydney at 288.3 U.S.
dollars an ounce from the December 31 close of 287.9.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 252.02 million shares traded at a value of 818.64
million Australian dollars (503.46 million U.S. dollars), with 568
gains, 522 falls and 369 others remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
