<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed higher on
the Singapore Stock Market Monday, opening the year on a promising
note as the market was boosted by a surprise cut in the prime
lending rate by the country's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) closed at 1,400.11,
rising 7.38 points from the half-day session on Thursday, the last
day of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 220.93 million units worth 236.83
million Singapore dollars (about 143.13 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers edged out losers by 204 to 50 with 166 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was a 15.9 million parcel of FlexTech which
transacted at 0.89 Singapore dollars per share. It was followed by
FlexTech w0 that had 14.05 million units traded. Brilliant was
next with 10.44 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 headed the ascent of the day with a jump of 130
cents to 24.6 Singapore dollars. DBS was next rising by 50 cents
to 15.4 Singapore dollars. Apac Brew gained 40 cents to finish at
3.82 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Shangri was the biggest loser of the day
shedding 36 cents to close at 2.32 Singapore dollars. SPH was next
retreating 30 cents to 17.7 Singapore dollars. DBS and SIA sank 20
cents and ended at 7.8 and 6.95 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Development Bank of Singapore Monday slashed its prime
lending rate by another half percentage point to 5 percent. The
move is likely to kick off the sixth round of cuts here since the
rates peaked last September.
</P>
<P>
The move was cheered on hope that property stocks would benefit
from cuts in interest rates
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the market shed some of its gains in the
afternoon, falling off its intraday high of 1,414.5 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
