<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Dollar Ends Stronger As Euro Makes Its Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar finished
a touch higher Monday after relinquishing center stage in local
trade to the debut of the euro - the world's first new currency in
three decades.
</P>
<P>
Attention was focused on Australia as the euro officially began
its first full trading day after being launched on January 1 as
the electronic currency of 11 of the 15 European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
Australia had been expecting the privilege of being the first
to trade the euro when markets opened here Monday, but rare New
Year's Day trading in India grabbed that honor.
</P>
<P>
At the close of local trade, the Australian dollar was buying
61.47 U.S. cents compared with 61.43 late New Year's Eve in local
business.
</P>
<P>
The local unit spent the day between 61.14 and 61.49 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
At 5am Monday morning the euro was trading at 1.1744 U.S. cents
and ended at 1.1746.
</P>
<P>
The euro was buying 1.9162 Australian dollars in early trading
and finished at 1.9109.
</P>
<P>
MMS Standard &AMP; Poor's currency strategist Alex Douglas said the
Australian dollar spent the day range-bound as attention was
focused on the euro.
</P>
<P>
"First up this morning most people's attentions were focused on
the launch of the euro and once that was out of the way I guess
for the start of the new year people were not so keen to jump in
and set new positions in the Aussie.
</P>
<P>
"Particularly so with the trade data due out tomorrow - people
are a bit hesitant ahead of the trade data."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Australian Bureau of Statistics will release
the balance of goods and services trade for November.
</P>
<P>
Economists' forecasts center on a 900 million Australian
dollars (553.5 million U.S. dollars) deficit.
</P>
<P>
Douglas said the outlook for the Australian dollar over the
next 24 hours was dependent on Tuesday's trade data.
</P>
<P>
"If the trade deficit is smaller than expected then Aussie
could have some quite significant gains."
</P>
<P>
At the close of local trading, the Australian dollar was at
69.72 Japanese yen from 70.51 on New Year's eve. And it was buying
0.3680 British pounds from 0.3685. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
