<HEADLINE> S. Lankan Rebels Give Ultimatum to Jaffna Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has issued a final warning to all local
government officials in the Jaffna Peninsula to resign immediately
from their positions, informed sources here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Failure to do so would be punishable by death, according to the
warning.
</P>
<P>
Under this situation, government officials in the peninsula in
the country's Northern province were prepared for such an
eventuality, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has also warned other local officials not to have any
dealing with the government troops.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna peninsula was once the stronghold of the LTTE
rebels, who have been waging a 16-year war for a separate state in
the north and east of the island country.
</P>
<P>
Having lost the peninsula to government forces in May 1996,
they have been pushed into jungle hideouts from where they have
been launching attacks on government troops and government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Later last month the LTTE gunned down the Tamil United
Liberation Front's Jaffna District Secretary Pon Mathimugarajah,
who was believed to be the next mayor of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE also assassinated two Jaffna mayors, Sarojini
Yogeswaran and P. Sivapalan, respectively in May and September
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Achieves Increased Tax Revenue Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China's State Administration of
Taxation (SAT) announced today that China had reached its target
of increasing industrial and commercial tax income by 100 billion
yuan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said that last year's tax revenues from the
industrial and commercial sector reached 855.1 billion yuan, an
increase of 13.3 percent or 100.3 billion yuan over that of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total revenues, domestic value-added tax and consumer
tax was 455.3 billion yuan, up 12.5 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the SAT said that the country's tax revenues
increased month by month in the second half of last year,
especially in the last two, which saw combined revenues of 191.2
billion yuan, constituting 22.4 percent of the year's total.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, in 1998 the ratio of industrial and
commercial tax revenues to 1998's gross domestic product was 10.7
percent, up 0.7 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
He said that measures adopted by the central government to
punish tax-related illegal practices had helped increase the
year's revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
