<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Central Bank Controls Finance Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Bank Negara Malaysia (BNM),
Malaysia's central bank, Monday assumed control of two finance
companies as part of its on-going effort to strengthen the banking
system.
</P>
<P>
The two finance companies, of which BNM assumed control with
effect from January 4, 1999, are MBf Finance, the country's
largest non-bank-owned finance company, and Kewangan Bersatu Bhd
(KBB), a finance company licensed under the Banking and Financial
Institutions Act (BAFIA).
</P>
<P>
In making the announcement in a statement here Monday, the
central bank said that with the assumption of control, MBf
Finance which requires recapitalization to improve its financial
health and to restore its risk weighted capital ratio to 8
percent, will be placed on a stronger financial position and its
board and management will also be strengthened while its viability
as a going concern will be restored.
</P>
<P>
The central bank appointed Low Ngiap Jin as the chief executive
officer who will be responsible for the day-to-day operations and
management of MBf Finance and appointed Hoh Kit Keong to manage
KBB's day-to-day operations, both with effect from January 4,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also assured depositors of the two companies
that all deposits are guaranteed by the government and that the
government will meet all deposit obligations (both principal and
interest payments) of all licensed finance companies and banking
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
