<HEADLINE> Twenty Private Firms Granted Trading Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty of China's private
businesses have been given permission to directly import and
export products, the first time this has been allowed.
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
(MOFTEC) announced the change in regulations today, which means
that private firms can now trade on equal terms with state or
collectively owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to MOFTEC officials, the registered capital of the 20
private manufacturers totaled 1.362 billion Yuan, averaging 68
million each.
</P>
<P>
They are engaged in such industries as animal feed, foodstuffs,
agricultural development, medicines, metallurgy, construction
materials, textiles, garment manufacture and retailing, light
industry, electronics and machinery and computer software
development.
</P>
<P>
China's largest animal feed producer, the Xiwang (Hope) Group
in southwest China's Sichuan Province was among them.
</P>
<P>
In total, seven Sichuan-based private manufacturers have been
granted trading licenses while in Shanghai, China's economic
center, five firms were on the approved list, Chengdu City
had four, two were from Beijing, while Guangdong and Jiangxi
provinces had one each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
