<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Following are the economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabian chemical and plastic industries
represent some 20 percent of the country's industrial production
and provide about 70 percent of the value of the country's
industrial exports.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a statistical report issued by the Saudi consultative
services agency, the Saudi Press Agency said Monday that the 616
chemical and plastic factories make up 19.8 percent of the 3,111
Saudi productive factories.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's foreign currency reserves reached 22.7
billion U.S. dollars in December, 1998, up 223 million dollars, or
nearly 1 percent, from 22.5 billion dollars in November, according
to the Bank of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Overall foreign currency reserves grew by 2.37 billion dollars
in 1998 as the local currency shekel's relatively high interest
rates attracted investors from abroad.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- World-leading accounting firm Price Waterhouse
Coopers (PWC) intends to set up a 50-million-dollar fund in Israel
to invest in Israel's high-teach and life-science companies, PWC's
global managing partner Jermyn Brroks said in Tel Aviv on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the PWC is willing to invest 1 billion dollars a year,
of which some 500 million dollars would be spent on improving the
technological abilities of the company.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government entered the new year of
1999 without a state budget as the budget bill failed to pass the
Knesset (parliament) in December, 1998. Accountant-general of the
Finance Ministry Shai Talmon said last week that the lack of a
budget for 1999 was a temporary setback and the nation could
survive January without one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
