<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police in Southern Philippines on Red Alert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- All police forces in Mindanao,
the southern Philippines, have been placed on red alert following
a grenade explosion in Jolo, Sulu, last Saturday, which killed 10
people and wounded 74 others, the Philippine News Agency said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Director General Roberto T. Lastimoso, acting
chief of the Philippine National Police (PNP), issued the order to
forestall any similar incident from happening.
</P>
<P>
Suspected members of the extremist Abu Sayyaf Group (ASG)
exploded a grenade inside a bakery in Downtown Jolo in an apparent
retaliation for the death of their leader, Abdurajak Janjalani, in
a gun battle with a police patrol in Basilan last December, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Lastimoso ordered PNP forces in General Santos City, Cotabato
City and Davao City to be very careful by stepping up their
intelligence gathering to detect any possible attack by Abu Sayyaf
members in their respective localities, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted the police chief as saying police visibility
in crowded areas must be maintained at all times to pre-empty
surprise attacks by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
All police forces in Mindanao must be alert and look for
possible presence of terrorists in their respective communities,
Lastimoso said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
