<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Expected to Import Less Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is expected to
import less rice this year than last year's 2.14 million tons
despite the lingering La Nina weather phenomenon, an official
said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency Monday quoted Agriculture Secretary
William Dar as saying typhoons, which are expected to visit the
country during the first half of 1999, will not have a substantial
effect on the country's major crops.
</P>
<P>
Irrigated areas are ensured of enough water for the next four
months and thus, rice production is seen to increase by 30 to 50
percent this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government aims to improve the self-sufficiency level of
grain from 92-96 percent to 98 percent to lower rice imports, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"However, should the 98 percent sufficiency level target is
attained, we may no longer import rice this year," Dar said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the agricultural sector is expected to recover
this year with a 2-3 percent growth rate from 1998's 1 percent
because of the El Nino and La Nina phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
He said the sector will be mainly spurred by increased rice and
corn output, poultry, livestock, coconut and fisheries sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
