<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Tax Revenue Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Last year the financial
revenues of Shanghai, China's leading industrial center, rose by
11 percent to 81.4 billion yuan over 1997.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises still remain the major source of revenues
with tax revenues from the local automobile industry alone
exceeding 3.6 billion yuan, while tax revenues from the service
sector grew rapidly, accounting for 55.5 percent of the city's
total.
</P>
<P>
Tax revenues from non-state-owned businesses continued to grow,
with ten foreign-funded enterprises each turning in over 100
million yuan in taxes.
</P>
<P>
Taxes turned in by more than 400,000 private businesses rose by
15 percent to 3.3 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
