<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Banks Set Dinar-Euro Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's commercial banks
have set their initial Kuwaiti dinar-euro exchange rate, with
analysts predicting the new currency will eventually change the
dinar's exchange rate mechanism.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspapers published Monday, National Bank
of Kuwait offered Sunday to buy one euro for 0.35090 Kuwaiti dinar
(KD) and sell it for KD 0.35540 and Burgan Bank offered KD
0.351889 and KD 0.355245.
</P>
<P>
Gulf Bank will set its first euro-dinar rate Monday.
</P>
<P>
The present exchange rate for U.S. dollar and dinar in Kuwait's
banks is 1 to 0.2990 for buy-in and 1 to 0.3045 for sell-out.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti banks said that they were prepared to deal in euros and
they had received a number of calls from interested traders,
individuals and speculators.
</P>
<P>
As the euro will coexist with the national currencies until
they become fully obsolete in mid-2002, customers with Kuwaiti
banks are free to keep their legacy accounts or have them
converted into a euro account.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts say the euro will affect trade between Kuwait
and European countries and ultimately affect the dinar exchange
rate mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Kuwait Economic Society Amer Al-Tameemi told
local daily the Kuwait Times that the euro will prompt the
Central Bank of Kuwait (CBK) to change its exchange rate
mechanism, but stressed this would only be a "technical" change
and will not greatly affect the value of dinar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
