<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increase in Agricultural Loans Boosts Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- There has been a sharp
increase in the number of farmers seeking loans from credit
cooperatives in southwest China's Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Most are used for agricultural schemes such as planting more
trees or undertaking water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
The increase is mainly attributed to the fact that the
land-contract policy in rural areas will remain unchanged for 30
years, which gives farmers a long tenure and encourages them to
invest in their land. The second round of allocating land
contracts has now been completed.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, agricultural credit cooperatives, in line with China's
banking policies, began to operate independently from the
Agricultural Bank of China and provide services solely to the
agricultural sector, which was then considered a poor market with
little potential.
</P>
<P>
Since then, there has been an impetus in the growth of small
towns and cities in the region due to the confirmed high status
given to agricultural activities throughout China and the State's
policy of increasing domestic demand, according to the Chongqing
Rural Economic Restructuring Office.
</P>
<P>
Credit cooperatives have now decided to expand their services
to include more infrastructure projects such as roads, electricity
grids and commercial housing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
