<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM Invited to Visit Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul
Ilah Al-Khatib has received an invitation from his Kuwaiti
counterpart Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah to visit the Gulf
emirate to end strains in bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Jordan Times Wednesday quoted Al-Khatib as
saying that he had received a message from Sheikh Sabah, inviting
him to visit Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Such a visit would officially end the strains in bilateral
relations which were severed following the 1990 Gulf Crisis,
Sheikh Sabah was quoted as saying by news agencies in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
However, the two sides has not set a specific date for the
visit.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, along with a few other Arab nations, sided with Iraq
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian embassy in Kuwait has been closed since then,
but the Kuwaiti mission in Amman headed by a charge d'affaires
remains open.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Jordan began to thaw in May 1995,
when Amman apparently distanced itself from Baghdad, and called
for political changes in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, then planning minister Rima Khalaf became the
first Jordanian cabinet minister to visit Kuwait after the
crisis, but the visit turned out to be highly symbolic with few
concrete results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
