<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT January 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK-- The Thai Transport and Communications Ministry is
asking for the cabinet's approval to let the private sector take
over the operation of 26 provincial airports which are currently
under the control of the Aviation Department, the Bangkok Post
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A government source was quoted as saying that the ministry
said the Aviation Department, as a state agency, was not flexible
enough to improve the operation of its provincial airports
because it had red-tape procedures in withdrawing budgets and
could not attract capable personnel due to its low salaries.
(Thailand-Aviation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GUILIN-- China expects its earnings from international and
domestic tourism in 1998 to amount to 343 billion yuan (41.3
billion US dollars), according to He Guangwei, chairman of the
National Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
That would be a year-on-year growth of 10.2 percent, he told
a national tourism meeting here, and said that the target for
1999 is 380 billion yuan. (China-Tourism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Senators of the United
States on Sunday voiced different opinions on a plan to expedite
the impeachment trial of President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Several senators said the president should consider delaying
his State of the Union address, scheduled for January 19, if the
trial is not wrapped up by that time.(US-Impeachment-Trial Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Two armed security guards were shot to death
while another two guards were critically wounded Sunday after a
shooting occurred at an apartment complex near downtown Los
Angeles, police said.(Los Angeles-Shooting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Phone service interrupted on Sunday to as many
as 75,000 customers in Las Vegas after three robbers wearing ski
masks broke into a telephone office, tied up workers and took
away computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted police spokesman Steve Meriwether
as saying that the robbers once took control of the telephone
office owned by Sprint, the third largest U.S. long-distance carr
ier, and shot Sprint employees with stun guns.
</P>
<P>
But the workers were not seriously injured, Meriwether
said.(US-Phone-Interruption)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD-- At least 16 people are reported to have been
killed and more than 20 others injured Monday morning when
terrorists sprayed bullets at a Shia mosque in central Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The assailants, armed with Kalashnikovs, emerged from a car at
about 6:45 a.m. and opened indiscriminate fire on a gathering of
the Shia sect at the Imambargah Qureshi, some 65 kilometers from
the central Pakistan town of Muzaffargarh, reports reaching here
said. (Pakistan-Killing) 
</P>
