<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Religious Leader Outlaws Use of Fireworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 4 (Xinhua) -- One of Lebanon's top religious
leaders has issued a religious edict, or Fatwa, outlawing the use
of fireworks as "sacrilegious," the Daily Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Sunday, Sayyed Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, spiritual leader of the Shiite Muslims community, the
country's largest single sect, said that people had spent a
sleepless night on New Year's Eve because the "merchants of
noise" had lured children into buying fireworks.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of harassment is sacrilegious because there is no
difference between storming someone's house and waking up people
violently and using fireworks on the streets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The leader said the use of fireworks encouraged children to
revel in an atmosphere of "backwardness unbecoming in all
civilized countries."
</P>
<P>
More than any other year since the end of the 1975-1990 civil
war, fireworks and tracer bullets lit up the skies of the capital
and other parts of the country on the New Year Eve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
