<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke010435   Manila Encourages Investment in Rural Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
drawing up an incentive package for investors willing to pour
their resources into the countryside in a bid to stimulate the
rural economy and create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here Monday, Undersecretary Melito Salazar
Jr. of the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) said a task
force created for this purpose will come up with recommendations
on a common incentive package to standardize the grant of these
benefits to potential rural investors.
</P>
<P>
The official said that at present the grant of incentives
varies depending on which government agency is handling a certain
project.
</P>
<P>
Incentives are usually granted to investors in economic zones,
the Subic Freeport and the Clark Special Economic Zone, he said.
</P>
<P>
Salazar said the incentives offered at the economic zones
include the duty-free importation of capital equipment.
</P>
<P>
In line with its program to drum up economic activity in the
countryside, the DTI has also revised its Investment Priorities
Plan (IPP) for 1999 to give local governments more influence in
determining the kind of development projects that will be set up
in their communities.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1999 IPP, the approval of proposed projects in a
certain community will depend on the economic benefits they will
generate, their relevance to social needs and their compliance
with environmental laws, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
