<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Krajicek Asks for More Details of Korda Doping Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Netherlands' former Wimbledon
champion Richard Krajicek said in Sydney on Monday the top
players should ask for more details concerning the Petr Korda
doping case.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time for the players to start asking questions
about what really happened," said the Dutch player, who will play
in the Sydney International tournament starting on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It's a very sensitive issue to talk about but I don't
understand it ... if he tested positive maybe he must have done
it but maybe there must be another side to the story," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Either you test positive or you don't and people should know
exactly what went on."
</P>
<P>
Korda, the Australian Open champion from the Czech Republic,
tested positive for the banned steroid nandrolone at last year's
Wimbledon championship but has said he is innocent.
</P>
<P>
The International Tennis Federation (ITF) announced the
positive test late last month and that Korda would be stripped of
his ranking points and the 94,529 U.S. dollars he earned in prize
money at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
However, the ITF said it would not ban Korda because it
believed him when he said he had not knowingly taken the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
