<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Childbirth Death Rate Amongst Shanghai Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to improved health
facilities, over the last two years China's largest city of
Shanghai has cut the death rate of women in childbirth to that of
most developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The number of women dying in childbirth is now only 12.48 per
100,000 people, compared to 13 per 100,000 in developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Prior to 1996, according to a report in the "Wenhui Daily", 62
out of every 100,000 pregnant women died in China's major coastal
cities before or during childbirth. This was still far below the
actual world average of 430 women per 100,000 and as many as 480
in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the mortality rate in China's poor rural areas is
still 200 per 100,000 women. Health officials blamed hemorrhaging,
hypertension, amniotic embolism, heart attacks, and inaccessible
maternity services as the major causes.
</P>
<P>
A national action program for child development has been
running in China throughout the 1990s and by the year 2000 the
national average death rate in childbirth is expected to have
fallen to about 95 women, half of the 1990 rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
