<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rules Simplified on Supply of Livestock, Frozen Commodities to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to increase the
mainland's market share of livestock and frozen foodstuffs sold
to Hong Kong, China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) has simplified pig supply procedures and
canceled the quotas on certain other products.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in the Ministry's influential
"International Business Daily," it will allow pig farms direct
access to the market, which was originally monopolized by trading
companies.
</P>
<P>
However, MOFTEC insists that those farms applying for an export
license must reach approved targets in their annual production.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the quality of the pigs will be guaranteed and breeding
methods be improved," said Liu Guosheng, an official with MOFTEC's
Department of Foreign Trade Administration.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry also intends to introduce the new export
procedures for other commodities if this trial period proves
successful.
</P>
<P>
It has already canceled the restrictive quotas for live ducks,
geese and pigeons, along with those for frozen ducks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
