<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Revenues Hit New High in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Last year industrial and
commercial tax revenues in south China's Guangdong Province jumped
by 11.2 percent over the 1997 figures to 114.97 billion yuan
(13.85 billion U.S. dollars), accounting for more than one-eighth
of the nation's total.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attributed the rise to the smooth operation of
Guangdong's economy during the year. In 1998, Guangdong's GDP grew
by 10.1 percent, with consumer retail sales rising by 11.3 percent
and individual savings deposits increasing by 120 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong taxation departments also intensified their
efforts to crack down on various kinds of financial malpractices
and tax evasion, which brought in additional tax revenue of more
than 4.4 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
