<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Diamond Exports Down 11.4 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's polished diamond
exports was 3.6 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, down 11.4 percent
from 4.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, according to data issued by
the Industry and Trade Ministry on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Imports of unpolished diamonds decreased 27 percent to 2.7
billion dollars in 1998, the ministry said, adding that imports of
polished diamonds grew 21 percent over 1997 to over one billion
dollars, reflecting the trend of shifting polishing process to
lower-wage countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel's diamond business was also affected by last year's
market crash in southeast Asia, it added.
</P>
<P>
The United States acquired 61 percent of Israel's exports in
1998, up from 50 percent in 1997, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The Asian market made up 19 percent of the polished diamond
exports market in 1998, while Europe remained steady at 17
percent, compared to 16 percent in 1997, the ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
