<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Build More Farm-to-Market Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
this year speed up a program to speed up the construction of
farm-to-market roads to energize the agricultural sector, an
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a report issued here, acting Agriculture Secretary William
Dar said 20 provinces in the country have released about 250
million pesos (6.25 million U.S. dollars) to build more than 250
kilometers of farm-to-market roads.
</P>
<P>
With nearly three-fourths of the country's poor dependent on
agriculture for employment and income, the government has given
utmost priority to modernizing agriculture, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's two-pronged objective is to improve
the quality of life of the agricultural workers and create
conditions favorable to them such as through the construction or
improvement of farm-to-market roads.
</P>
<P>
In addition to hastening the construction of farm-to-market
roads, the Estrada administration has also intensified
agricultural support services, Dar said.
</P>
<P>
According to Dar, his department has distributed 23 units of
outdoor storage equipment, 885 moisture meters, 12 in-store
dryers, 17 electric grain dryers, five tobacco flu-curing dryers
and 274 units of multi-purpose drying pavements or solar dryers to
thousands of farmers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Farm equipment like hand tractors, thresher-shelters, threshers
 and stripper-harvesters was also distributed to farmers and
cooperatives, Dar added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
