<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Sacrifice Found in 5,000-year-old Ruin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The remains of a human, sacrificed
in an ancient religious ceremony, have been discovered in the
foundations of a house approximately 5,000 years old in Tengzhou
city in east China's Shandong province.
</P>
<P>
There is evidence that the victim was tied up and that the
incident dates back to the late Dawenkou Culture, which historians
say was prevalent in the region maybe some 6,300 to 4,500 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Local archaeologists say it is an unusual find as similar
discoveries from that period only involved pigs.
</P>
<P>
The ancient ruins are located in a village where both domestic
living quarters and tombs were mixed.
</P>
<P>
According to the archaeologists, they have so far unearthed
about 20 tombs but found only limited amounts of pottery,
indicating that the locals were poor, which were buried with the
dead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
