<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Good or Bad, Child Marriage Common in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- When Rita Luintel was just 14
years old, her parents married her off against her own will.
</P>
<P>
"Though I'm happy now with my two-year-old son and husband who
is very helpful and takes care of me, I have the feeling that
marriage should not be done before 20 as said in the TV and
radio," 18-year-old Luintel told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"It is not good to marry at an early age," she held. "I
attended primary school only but my parents married me at the age
of 14."
</P>
<P>
"I listened to the radio and TV and they say that it is not
good to marry before 20. I wanted to study. But what could I do?"
said Luintel who lives in a village in the Kathmandu Valley,
Nepal's most developed area.
</P>
<P>
She is only one of the thousands bounded in child marriage, an
age-old practice in the Himalayan kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"The history of child marriage in Nepal goes back to the
ancient times," Rishi Keshiv Regmi, professor of sociology at the
Tribhuvan University, said.
</P>
<P>
He said parents think that they have fulfilled their
responsibilities after they marry their children off at a young
age.
</P>
<P>
Lal Bahadur Tamang living in a village in Kathmandu is a father
with a similar mindset.
</P>
<P>
"It is not good to keep daughters for a long time," he said.
"They are supposed to be given to others. Then why should we take
their responsibility?"
</P>
<P>
"There is a fear with the grownup daughter all the time until
she is married," he explained. "It is good to marry at an early
age. I could not send her to school because of my poverty."
</P>
<P>
"Now I'm satisfied because I fulfilled my responsibility," he
added. "I myself, my brothers and sisters also married before the
age of 15."
</P>
<P>
But it seems unlikely that his fear ends there because three
other daughters are still living under his roof.
</P>
<P>
Professor Regmi attributed child marriage to the lack of
knowledge and awareness.
</P>
<P>
"The literacy rate of Nepal is very low and this is very very
low in the remote western part of the country so they don't have
knowledge about at what age they should marry their children," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Superstition, religion and tradition have also played an
important role for this trend," he added.
</P>
<P>
He continued to say child marriage used to be found in every
part of the country until some years ago. It is now popular
particularly in the western part of the country and other remote
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Most of the people in the rural areas want to marry their sons
earlier so that they can help them in their work, he said, adding
that the practice exists as well in urban areas where people live
in poverty.
</P>
<P>
He noted that after the introduction in 1964 of the Civil Code
prohibiting the marriage of girls and boys aged below 16 and 18
respectively, the cases of child marriage have been going down
slowly in the country.
</P>
<P>
He believed that with the spread of education and the effective
implementation of the law, the child marriage system will come to
an end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
