<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Easier Access to South China's Pearl River Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- A highway network is taking
shape in the Pearl River Delta, an economic powerhouse in south
China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, the people of Hong Kong needed 4 hours to go to
Guangzhou, Guangdong's capital, from Shenzhen, the country's first
special economic zone near Hong Kong, but it only takes an hour
and a half now and the Delta area is becoming smaller.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has built a highway network to link
Guangzhou with Shenzhen, Sanshui, Huadu, Shantou, Foshan and
Kaiping since August of 1989. Now the province is crisscrossed by
a total of 785 kilometers of higheays.
</P>
<P>
In the Pearl River Delta, the highways used to be separated by
rivers, which seriously affected the transport of raw materials
and finished products and local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the provincial government introduced
market competition for highway construction and developed various
ways of raising funds. In the past two decades, it allocated two
billion yuan (about 250 million U.S. dollars) annually for highway
construction.
</P>
<P>
According to provincial transportation department officials, by
2000, Guangdong will have 1,800 kilometers of highways and all
prefecture-level cities will be connected.
</P>
<P>
And, by 2010, a network centered on Guangzhou will connect
national trunk lines, major cities, transportation hubs, and
ports, and cargo from anywhere in the province can reach harbors
within 24 hours.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
