<HEADLINE> School in Southwest China Merges Two Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- A public school in Sichuan, a
populous province in southwest China, has managed to merge two
debt-ridden state-owned enterprises, according to the school
leaders.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release from Chengdu's Xinjin-Huarun School
on its fifth anniversary on December 28, 1998, county authorities
have given it the green light, on a deal backed by Xinjin County
and Hong Kong's China Resources Co. Ltd., to merge the Xinjin Silk
Co. and Xinjin Agriculture Co., which have been losing money for a
long time.
</P>
<P>
The school began paying all debts carried by the two
enterprises last September and has helped all 98 workers get jobs
in the school and has helped them with medical insurance and their
overdue wages.
</P>
<P>
On the original land of the enterprises, the school has erected
an auditorium and a sports center and is planning to develop real
estate and shops.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the fixed assets of the school have jumped
from 3.7 million yuan (about 462,500 U.S. dollars) to 90 million
yuan. 
</P>
