<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Supreme Court Orders Postponement of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of the
Philippines, ordered Monday the postponement of the execution of
rape-convict Leo Echegaray, the first in the country's history,
from Monday afternoon to June 15, 1999, to allow the congress to
review the Death Penalty Law.
</P>
<P>
Supreme Court, Clerk of Court Luzviminda Puno said here that as
provided for under a two-page resolution, the High Court will no
longer entertain any motion of whatever kind after June 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
She said the high court ruled to allow the postponement in
order for the Senate and the House of Representatives to determine
the wisdom of the Death Penalty Law.
</P>
<P>
Puno said there was no stay of execution but a mere
postponement, meaning the high court has not reversed its decision
maintaining the constitutionality of the death penalty law until
and when it is repealed.
</P>
<P>
All of the 13 justices of the high court participated in the
deliberations Monday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
