<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tackling Lake Pollution in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Anhui Province in east China is
set to improve the water quality of Chaohu Lake, around which are
109 enterprises, each of them producing more than 100 tons of
waste water every day.
</P>
<P>
All the factories in the valleys will have to meet state
emission standards by the end of this year, according to a
provincial government official.
</P>
<P>
Chaohu Lake, one of China's five largest freshwater lakes, has
been seriously polluted in the past several years because of rapid
economic development in the region. Environmental officials say
that the government will help enterprises raise funds and develop
technology to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
Factories that have no hope of meeting state emission standards
will be shut down and have production changed as soon as possible,
the official says.
</P>
<P>
The province has banned new projects that will cause pollution
in the lake valleys.
</P>
<P>
A loan of some 140 million U.S. dollars from the Asian
Development Bank will be used in dealing with the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
