<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi, Indian Officials Start Joint Monitoring of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Officials of Bangladesh and India
Sunday started joint monitoring of the Ganges flow at Hardinge
Bridge point located in Bangladesh's western district of Pabna,
two days after the commencement of current lean period, The
Financial Express daily newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides would observe the flow of the Ganges (Padma) at
six places near Hardinge Bridge point as stipulated in the 30-year
Indo-Bangladesh Ganges Water-Sharing Treaty signed in December
1996, the report quoted official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of the joint monitoring, the flow of the Padma
at the point was 129,211 cusecs (cubic foot per second) water
compared to 157,517 cusecs on the same day in 1998 and 79,460
cusecs in 1997, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is to get 67,516 cusecs of water during the first
10-day cycle from January 1, according to the water-sharing
treaty.
</P>
<P>
The flow of the Ganges water will be jointly monitored during
the lean period up to March 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
