<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Builds One More Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- One more dam, the Hsinthe Dam,
has been commissioned into service in Myanmar's Mandalay division,
bringing the total number of dams and reservoirs built since 1988
to 92.
</P>
<P>
The Hsinthe Dam, inaugurated on Sunday in Tatkon township of
the central and arid division, would irrigate over 12,960 hectares
of land and benefit about 21,060 hectares of crop land, official
The New Light of Myanmar newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The dam would also supply water for drinking and prevent floods
of Hsinthe Creek.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Second Secretary of the Myanmar State Peace
and Development Council Lieutenant-General Tin Oo as saying that
dams and diversion weirs have emerged one after another in the
arid zone.
</P>
<P>
Water-pumping projects have been carried out and agricultural
works can be extended in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Farm land in the arid zone have been turned into paddy fields
and the farmers who had no experience in cultivating paddy have
been engaged in paddy cultivation, he said, adding that the
government is not only giving priority to works for availability
of water, but also making efforts to improve agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
Of the 92 dams built since 1988, ten were constructed during
1997 and 1998 with 216,067 hectares irrigated. There were 23 dams
in Mandalay division.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar registered a 4.6 percent growth of its gross domestic
product (GDP) in the 1997-98 fiscal year, in which agriculture,
the mainstay of the country's economy, grew by 2.9 percent in
output value, accounting for 35.6 percent of the total GDP and
about 35 percent of the export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
