<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Prepares to Meet EU Standards in Fish Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has set up a special
unit to inspect and ensure the required quality standards of fish
exports to the European Union (EU), officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new unit functions under the Ministry of Fisheries and
Aquatic Resources Development which has been appointed as the
competent authority for the health control of fishery products,
said a ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
This follows representations by the EU that Sri Lanka should
maintain several guidelines to ensure quality of fish products if
it desires to continue to export fish to European countries
without being included in the list of banned countries.
</P>
<P>
The unit will undertake inspection activities with regard to
land sites and vessels, said the spokesman, adding that fisheries
harbors are being restructured in accordance with EU directives.
</P>
<P>
Laboratories servicing the fishing industry will be accredited
in accordance with International Standardization/Standards
Organization (ISO) Guide 25.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen will also be trained to hygienically handle fish on
board fishing vessels, the spokesman said. 
</P>
