<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Industrial Sector Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's industrial sector
has achieved a significant 14 percent growth in rupee terms during
the first ten months of 1998, the Central Bank disclosed Monday.
</P>
<P>
During this period industrial export earnings contributed 187
billion rupees (2.75 billion U.S. dollars) to the country's total
export earnings of 251 billion rupees (3.69 billion dollars), the
bank said.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials said this had been achieved when most other
countries in Asia were undergoing economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In order to boost exports the government has offered
industrialists alluring incentives as well as all other support
during the last four years.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of the reduction of the duty on capital goods,
local industrialists have imported 75 billion rupees (1.1 billion
dollars) worth of machinery and equipment.
</P>
<P>
According to the Central Bank, industrial exports -- the food,
beverages and tobacco sector recorded an impressive 60 percent
growth and earned 6.4 billion rupees (94.1 million dollars) during
the first ten months of 1998 against 4 billion rupees (58.8
million dollars) during the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The textiles and apparel sector recorded an 18.7 percent growth
while leather and rubber products also recorded an 18.7 percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture exports grew by 16.2 percent. Tea and minor
agriculture crop exports contributed to the growth of agricultural
exports earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
