<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Telecom Sector to Tackle Y2K Bug by June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Telecom service providers in Sri
Lanka aim to tackle the year 2000 Millennium Bug or Y2K issue by
June this year, according to a report by the Telecommunications
Regulatory Commission of Sri Lanka (TRCSL).
</P>
<P>
In its report presented to President Chandrika Kumaratunga
recently, the TRCSL said that it was satisfied with the work done
by most of the telecom service providers to tackle the problem,
the Island newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report was based on a questionaire distributed to all
service providers by TRCSL focusing on key issues.
</P>
<P>
The response from fixed-access operators, cellular phone
operators, data communications operators and paging operators was
satisfactory, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report said all operators were requested to test their
networks for Y2K readiness before December 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Random audits to check Y2K readiness of all the licensed
telecommunication operators will be done by the TRCSL in order to
reach full Y2K compliance by June, the report added. 
</P>
