<HEADLINE> Former Heavyweight Boxer Jerry Quarry Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Jerry Quarry, a former
American heavyweight boxer, died in Templeton, California on
Sunday after being taken off life support at the request of his
family. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
Quarry was hospitalized on December 28 with pneumonia and then
suffered cardiac arrest while at Twin Cities Community Hospital.
</P>
<P>
He died after family members directed doctors to remove life
support.
</P>
<P>
Quarry finished his career with a 53-9-4 record including
fight with Muhammad Ali and Floyd Patterson after having fighting
more than 200 bouts as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
Among the highlights of Quarry's career were two fights
against Patterson, the former heavyweight champion. The first
ended in a draw and he won the second on a controversial split
decision.
</P>
<P>
Quarry, 1.83-meter and 88-kilogram, earned his biggest payday,
338,000 dollars, by fighting Ali.
</P>
<P>
The pounding he had taken in his boxing life caused severe
damage to his brain, turning him into a confused, childlike man
by the age of 50. 
</P>
