<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Begins Cautious Trade in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The euro, Europe's new single
currency, started formal trading in Sydney Monday morning quietly
and cautiously.
</P>
<P>
Australia was to have been the site of the first official trade
in the euro but India jumped the gun and traded the new currency
on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
As it was, trading in Sydney was quiet with many foreign
exchange dealers hesitant to take positions in a currency with no
history.
</P>
<P>
The new European currency first traded in Sydney at 1.1744 U.S.
dollars almost level with the expected rate of 1.1668 U.S.
dollars, and 1.91828 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Australian Financial Services Minister Joe Hockey said Monday
Australia's status as a regional financial center was boosted by
the start of trade in the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Hockey said the eyes of the world's major central banks and
financial institutions were on Australia.
</P>
<P>
"Our time zone advantage over Singapore and Hong Kong was not
lost on world financial markets this morning," Hockey said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Trade in the euro appeared to go smoothly from the open of the
local market at 5 a.m. Monday local time (18:00, Sunday GMT).
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia's foreign exchange desk was
more heavily staffed than usual and one dealer said despite the
slow start the euro was very liquid.
</P>
<P>
But, he said a lot of that could be attributed to participants
simply wanting to be trading on the first day.
</P>
<P>
By 6 a.m., the new currency had traded to a high of 1.1750 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The open of the local interbank market at 6 a.m. was quiet but
dealers expected it to pick up as the day proceeds.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Investment Bank head of foreign exchange John Reedyk told
the Australian Associated Press that trade in the euro so far in
the morning had been moderate.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the main participants in the trade in Sydney were
international banks such as ABN Amro and Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
Eleven of the European Union's 15 members have adopted the
euro: Austria, Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy,
Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Denmark and Sweden have decided to wait and see before
joining the currency and Greece was refused membership after it
failed to meet the stringent economic targets set by the Union.
</P>
<P>
From midnight on New Year's Eve, the 11 national currencies
ceased to exist as separate currencies and became subdivisions of
the euro.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, the hard currency of the euro will not be
released until January 2002 and notes and coins of the national
currencies will remain in circulation until June that year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
