<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senators Differ on Plan to Expedite Clinton Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Senators of the United
States on Sunday voiced differing opinions on a plan to expedite
the impeachment trial of President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Several senators said the president should consider delaying
his State of the Union address, scheduled for January 19, if the
trial is not wrapped up by that time.
</P>
<P>
"I think it would be unseemly and distracting for the
president to be giving a State of the Union address to Congress
while he was under trial in the Senate," Senator Slade Gorton, a
Republican, told NBC's "Meet the Press".
</P>
<P>
Gorton and Senator Joseph Lieberman, a Democrat, were the
first to conceive of the bipartisan plan for a condensed
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which was later floated by the Senate's Majority L
eader Trent Lott, would allow for an early "test vote" to see
whether the required two-thirds of senators would back the
president's ouster if the substance of allegations in the Monica
Lewinsky case were proven true.
</P>
<P>
The vote would be taken after summary arguments from both
sides and no witnesses would need to be called. If the
preliminary vote failed to show support for expelling Clinton,
the Senate could then move on to consider censure.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has been searching for a resolution to the impeach
ment issue after the Republican-dominated House of
Representatives, in a vote cast mostly along party lines,
approved last month two articles of impeachment charging Clinton
with lying under oath and obstructing justice. Both charges stem
from his affair with Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
Democratic senators expressing their views on Sunday's talk
shows were generally supportive of the bipartisan proposal that
Lott has been working on with Senate Democratic Leader Tom
Daschle.
</P>
<P>
But there were different views among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
Senator Thad Cochran, a Republican, said he personally would
endorse the Lott compromise, but said it will need to be
discussed among other senators. "If it isn't acceptable then we
may have to make amendments to it or changes to it to accommodate
all senators," he told CBS's "Face the Nation" program.
</P>
<P>
Republican Senator Phil Gramm said on "Meet the Press" that a
trial was needed because the president, although acknowledging an
improper relationship with Lewinsky, has disputed charges that he
lied under oath and obstructed justice. "We've got to hear from
both sides to do justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Senator Arlen Specter, another Republican, who had said
publicly in the past he did not think removing Clinton was in the
nation's best interests, said senators nevertheless had a duty to
hold a trial and complete it with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
The new 106th Congress is set to convene on January 6. One of
the first orders of business in the Senate will be to swear in
the 100 members as jurors in the Clinton trial.
</P>
<P>
House Republicans who will serve as "managers" -- or
essentially prosecutors -- of the Senate trial already have
criticized Lott's idea of an expedited trial followed by a "test"
impeachment vote, saying it would deprive them of the chance to
make their case.
</P>
<P>
But Senator Patrick Leahy, a Democrat, said House Republicans
had shown "condescending arrogance" and accused them of trying to
meddle in the Senate's decision on how to conduct the trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Suceeds in Breeding More Giant Pandas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chengdu Giant Panda Breeding
Research Base in China's Sichuan Province has used artificial
insemination to produce 45 giant pandas, with 27 surviving more
than 6 months.
</P>
<P>
After more than 10 years of efforts by researchers, according
to Yu Jianqiu, a specialist in the field, the simulated wild
environment of the base has allowed researchers to do a
comprehensive study of breeding and illness prevention of giant
pandas and develop artificial insemination technology.
</P>
<P>
Twelve zoos and one animal reserve in the world have bred about
140 giant pandas with a much lower surviving rate, 29 percent,
though, since China used artificial insemination to breed the
first baby in 1963. The 30-hectare base in the northern suburb of
Chengdu has been developing breeding technology since it used
frozen semen for artificial insemination in 1980.
</P>
<P>
All naturally born giant pandas and 80 percent of those
produced by artificial inseminations have been able to have
babies. Giant pandas only have one or two babies each time. Less
than 10 percent of the base's males and 24 percent of the females
are able to mate by themselves.
</P>
<P>
There are only about 1,000 pandas in existence, in China's
Sichuan, Gansu, and Shaanxi provinces, 80 percent of them in
Sichuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Cocoa Production Expected to Bounce Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's cocoa production is
expected to recover in 1999 after being hit by a severe dry spell
caused by El Nino, the Jakarta Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's cocoa production is expected to reach 330,000 tons
in 1999, a 6-percent increase compared to the 310,000 tons
produced last year.
</P>
<P>
"The effect of the La Nina weather phenomenon for this year's
cocoa harvest will not be as drastic as El Nino's. If the weather
condition continues to be favorable for cacao trees, I believe
that our cocoa output could reach 330,000 tons in 1999," executive
director of the Indonesian Cocoa Association P.S. Siswoputranto
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the effects of the 1998 El Nino-caused
drought, the drop in the country's cocoa output in 1998 was not as
extreme as predicted.
</P>
<P>
"We expected that production in 1998 would at least reach the
1997's level of 307,000 tons. But we are still gathering data from
the provinces, and we believe that cocoa production might increase
slightly to 310,000 tons for 1998," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the El Nino cycle in 1997/1998, Indonesia experienced
its most severe drought in 50 years. The country could only
produce 307,000 tons of cocoa beans in 1997, far below its initial
forecast of 330,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino weather phenomenon is an abnormal weather system in
the tropical Pacific Ocean which triggers exceptionally warm and
long-lived ocean currents which disrupt global rainfall and wind
patterns and cause droughts or flooding across the globe.
</P>
<P>
La Nina is brought about by unusually cool temperatures in the
Pacific Ocean and often follows the drought-inducing El Nino. Its
arrival brings more rain and violent tropical storms.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is currently the world's third largest cocoa producer
after Cote d'Ivoire and Ghana with an output of 317,000 tons of
cocoa beans in 1996, or about 10 percent of the world's supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
