<HEADLINE> Private Sector in Hunan Province Helps Jobless Find Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- In 1998, the private sector in
Hunan Province, central China, has become a major means of easing
the unemployment pressure of people laid off from state and
collectively-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of the laidoff workers have found jobs in
private enterprises, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
By November, private enterprises in the province had taken over
some 2,000 state and collectively-owned enterprises through
mergers or leasing agreements, helping 300,000 people get jobs.
And, the skills and discipline of the former employees of state and
collectively-owned enterprises are welcome in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
And the provincial government has also issued licenses for
200,000 laidoff workers.
</P>
<P>
Because of the improved management and distribution systems in
the private sector, these workers have a more positive attitude
toward their work and earn more.
</P>
<P>
Many have set up their own businesses. Cao Zhibin, who was let
go by a sock factory, established the Yiyang Yinbin Sock
Factory by raising 140,000 yuan (about 17,500 U.S. dollars) and
gave jobs to 30 laidoff workers. In 1998, the factory
earned one million yuan and paid taxes of 20,000 yuan. 
</P>
