<HEADLINE> Ukrainian PM Vows to Stabilize Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko has vowed to take whatever it takes to keep the
country's currency stable this year.
</P>
<P>
In talking to the Ukrainian Interfax news agency Saturday,
Pustovoitenko said the stabilization of Hrivnia is mandated by
the 1999 budget law passed on December 31.
</P>
<P>
While adopting the legislation, the Supreme Soviet, or
parliament, recently has also set forth principles for monetary
and credit policies, said the head of government.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, he said, these measures would allow people to know
clearly about the fluctuation of the exchange rate of Hrivnia
against U.S. dollar throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
The rate was 1.8-2.25 Hrivnias to one dollar January through
July in 1998, and then 2.5-3.5 Hrivnias to one dollar in
September in the wake of Russia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
For now, the country's central bank has managed to keep the
exchange rate at around 3.427 Hrivnias to the dollar for more
than two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
