<HEADLINE> China's Tourism Predicted at 10.2 Percent Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, January 4 (Xinhua) -- China expects its earnings from
international and domestic tourism in 1998 to amount to 343
billion yuan (41.3 billion US dollars), according to He Guangwei,
chairman of the National Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
That would be a year-on-year growth of 10.2 percent, he told a
national tourism meeting here, and said that the target for 1999
is 380 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
There will be an all-out effort to expand the domestic market
and improve the industry's quality in the new year, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China had 62.5 million overseas tourists and earned
12.5 billion U.S. dollars from the business, up by 8.5 and
3.5 percent, respectively, and 659 million Chinese travelled
around the country in 1998, bringing in 239 billion yuan in
revenues. These are year-on-year increases of 2.4 and 13.2
percent, respectively. 
