<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji said China's modernization practice has
proved that economic progress highes on the growth of science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The premier, who also heads a government leading group for
scientific and technological education, made the remark at the
group's third meeting held in Beijing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that important tasks now center on advancing
refrom of scientific, technological and educational systems, as
well as accelerating development of practical innovations.
</P>
<P>
-- Statistics show that China received 62.5 million overseas
tourists last year, earning 12.5 billion U.S. dollars. Plus
domestic tourism revenue, China expected to earn in 1998 a total
tourism income of 343 billion yuan (41 billion U.S. dollars), up
10.2 percent over 1997. China is expected to make 380 billion yuan
(45.94 billion U.S. dollars) from tourism industry this year.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegram"
</P>
<P>
-- China on Friday began to impose the world's toughest land
use regulations to protect arable land through the implementation
of the revised "Land Use Law" in an effort to ensure sustainable
economic and social progress.
</P>
<P>
The new law requires that each province, autonomous region and
municipality guarantee that the amount of arable land under their
jurisdiction does not decrease, and that land quality is improved
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
-- Over a million of flood victims in east China's Jiangxi
Province have been provided adequate food and clothing while the
grain output in the province reduced by 2.1 billion kilograms this
year.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The country's top legislature, the National People's
Congress (NPC), has concluded the drafting and revising of 89 laws
in its four-year legislation program.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth NPC Standing Committee will draft and examine 63 laws
before its term of office expires in 2002.
</P>
<P>
-- The nation's 160,000 procurators lived up to their
collective reputation as society's watchdog in 1998 -- a year
highlighted by crackdowns on smuggling and
foreign-exchange-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
Procuratorates, China's prosecuting organs, handled 263
smuggling and foreign-exchange related cases last year involving
566 suspects, indicates the Supreme People's Procuratorate.
</P>
