<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Killed as Floods Blanket 6 Provinces in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Floods hit at least six
provinces in Indonesia over the weekend, causing seven deaths in
North and South Sulawesi as of late Sunday, the Jakarta Post
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead were a mother and her four-year-old child who
were swept away by the raging water in Barru regency. Another
person drowned in Maros regency, the report quoted witnesses as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Barru and Maros regencies, important rice producing areas in
South Sulawesi province, are respectively located around 100 and
30 kilometers north of the provincial capital of Ujungpandang.
</P>
<P>
The rain, which has fallen since New Year's Eve on Thursday,
inundated dozens of residential sites, bridges, roads and other
facilities, including the Indonesian Muslim University and the
nearby University 45.
</P>
<P>
In North Sulawesi province, four were killed when landslides
caused by torrential rains buried their houses in Liwas, Ranomuut
village, early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The latest casualties added to the death toll caused by
widespread floods in Indonesia. Last Friday, eight people died and
13 were injured when a flash flood hit a gold mining areas in
Bengkulu province, Sumatera.
</P>
<P>
In Serang, West Java province, at least 310 houses and 300
hectares of rice fields were immersed by water that reached one
meter high.
</P>
<P>
As of Saturday, two paper factories were floods in the Kragilan
subdistrict, which was among the worst hit by flooding in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Surabaya, East Java province, as of Saturday the eastern
part of the town was still experiencing water between 20
centimeters and 80 centimeters high. Heavy rain has fallen
unremittingly in the city since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In Samarinda, East Kalimantan province, at least 175 hectares
of rice fields in Lempake and five hectares of corn fields in the
Sempaja subdistrict were swamped, causing damage to about 60
percent of the rice plants.
</P>
<P>
In Pekalongan, Central Java province, at least 134 houses were
damaged by landslides in the Kendangserang district on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990104.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dongguan City Enjoys Double-Digit Export Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 4 (Xinhua) -- The city of Dongguan in south
China's Guangdong Province exported products valued at over 11.19
billion US dollars during the first 11 months of 1998, up 22.21
percent on the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The export growth rate was 22 percentage points higher than the
national rate in spite of the negative impact of the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dongguan, which accounts for 6.8 percent of China's total
exports, is situated between Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong
Province, and Shenzhen, the forerunner in the nation's reform and
opening drive.
</P>
<P>
The city, one of China's largest export processing and
manufacturing bases, is home to 13,000 companies engaged in related
production. Dongguan's processing sector exported products valued
at over 10.67 billion US dollars during the 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shunguang, director of the Dongguan Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Commission, attributed the city's
double-digit export growth to the 1995 implementation of a
strategy to upgrade the processing industry.
</P>
<P>
Dongguan has shifted from developing labor-intensive industries
to expanding the fund- and technology-intensive sectors which
feature high valued-added value and in-depth processing services,
as well as from assembling imported components to manufacturing
products according to buyer specifications.
</P>
<P>
Dongguan also approved 1,246 overseas-funded projects during
the first 11 months, with total investments rising 10.94 percent
to slightly over 1.23 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city has expanded its the traditional exports market in
Southeast Asia to the United States, the European Union, and
Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
