<HEADLINE> Kleinschmidt Leads Dakar Auto Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 3 (Xinhua) -- Jutta Kleinschmidt, the first
woman to win a stage in the Dakar rally two years ago, shone in
this year's event again when she took the overall lead in the
third stage between Agadir and Tan Tan, Morocco, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The German, driving a Mitsubishi, beat team mate Hiroshi
Masuoka by two minutes and 18 seconds for her second victory
after winning in Oclan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
She took advantage of mishaps to her team leaders at rocky 230
kilometers stretch in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi leaders Jean-Pierre Fontenay from France and
Japan's Kenjiro Shinozuka, winners for the last two years, all
suffered from punctures of tires. Fontenay was seventh and
Shinozuka 10th.
</P>
<P>
In the mortorcycle category, overall leader Joan Roma of Spain
enhanced his position by beating KTM team mate Heinz Kinigadner
of Austria.
</P>
<P>
Roma clocked two hours 14 minutes and seven seconds, more than
one minute ahead of Kinigadner in second place.
</P>
<P>
Monday's fourth stage takes the caravan to Mauritania in a
515-kms fourth stage to Bir Mogrein. 
</P>
</TEXT>
